export const PIPELINE = [
  { id:"s01", stage:"01", label:"Gene Construction", sub:"Molecular Biology", icon:"🧬", accent:"#C084FC",
    topics:[
      { id:"t01a", title:"Codon Optimization",
        body:"CHO cells prefer certain codons — suboptimal usage causes ribosomal stalling and dramatically lower titer. Codon optimization replaces rare CHO codons with preferred alternatives computationally before de novo gene synthesis. Studies show 3–10× titer improvements from optimization alone.",
        why:"Codon optimization locks in the manufacturing productivity ceiling before any other CMC decision. Poor codon usage limits titer to under 1 g/L vs. 5–10 g/L achievable with optimized sequences — worth hundreds of millions over a product lifecycle.",
        how:"Read Gustafsson et al. 2004 (Science 304:1392). Compare original vs. optimized sequence Codon Adaptation Index (CAI) scores. Ask your mentor: what titer uplift did optimization produce?",
        ref:"ICH Q11 §3.2.S.2.1 | ICH Q5B | Gustafsson et al. Science 2004;304:1392-5" },
      { id:"t01b", title:"Expression Vector Design",
        body:"The optimized gene is cloned into a vector containing: promoter (CMV/EF1α/CAG), Kozak sequence, signal peptide, selection marker (GS or DHFR), poly-A signal. For mAbs, heavy and light chains are typically on separate transcription units. Vector architecture profoundly affects expression level and genetic stability.",
        why:"The vector is a BLA-registered manufacturing raw material. Every element is filed in the IND and BLA — changes after first GMP manufacture require comparability data and potentially a new regulatory filing.",
        how:"Ask to see the expression vector map. Read ICH Q5B on expression construct analysis. Research GS-knockout CHO vs. DHFR-deficient CHO-DG44 selection system differences.",
        ref:"ICH Q5B | ICH Q11 | FDA Phase 1 CMC Guidance (2014)" },
      { id:"t01c", title:"QTPP — Foundation of QbD",
        body:"The Quality Target Product Profile defines desired drug product characteristics linked to clinical intent: dosage form, route, strength, CQA targets, container-closure, and shelf life. All CMC activities should trace back to a QTPP element. It is drafted at program start and updated as understanding grows.",
        why:"Starting without a QTPP means CMC activities lack a unified quality goal. Regulators expect QTPP-driven QbD thinking throughout Module 3. Retrospectively connecting CMC data to a QTPP post-BLA is extremely difficult.",
        how:"Read ICH Q8(R2) Annex 1 for a QTPP template. Study the A-Mab Case Study QTPP example. Draft a one-page QTPP for a hypothetical mAb before continuing to CQA identification.",
        ref:"ICH Q8(R2) | A-Mab Case Study (CASSS 2009)" },
      { id:"t01d", title:"Developability Assessment — Sequence Liabilities",
        body:"In silico and biophysical tools identify CMC liabilities before CLD investment: CDR deamidation hotspots (Asn-Gly, Asn-Ser), oxidation-prone Met/Trp in CDRs, isomerization-prone Asp-Pro sequences, N-glycosylation sites in CDRs, and aggregation-prone regions (APRs). Tools include CamSol, SAP scoring, IMGT/V-QUEST for germline analysis, and biophysical screens (DLS, CSI-ELISA).",
        why:"Failing in developability screens is cheap — weeks and milligrams. Failing after 18 months of CLD because CDR deamidation creates a heterogeneous, unstable CQA is catastrophic and can terminate a program.",
        how:"Read Jarasch et al. MAbs 2015;7:452. Run the antibody sequence through CamSol or BioPharma Finder for APR prediction. Ask your mentor: what sequence changes were made based on developability screening?",
        ref:"ICH Q8 | Jarasch et al. MAbs 2015;7:452-60 | Chennamsetty et al. PNAS 2009;106:11937" },
      { id:"t01e", title:"Signal Peptide Selection and Cleavage Verification",
        body:"The signal peptide directs the nascent protein to the ER for secretion. Choice affects mRNA stability, translocation efficiency, and signal peptidase cleavage accuracy. Native IgG signal peptides vs. optimized synthetic sequences show measurable productivity differences. Signal peptide cleavage must be confirmed by N-terminal sequencing of purified drug substance.",
        why:"Incomplete or incorrect signal peptide cleavage generates N-terminal extension heterogeneity that must be characterized as a CQA and monitored. FDA expects N-terminal sequence confirmation in the BLA.",
        how:"Review your signal peptide design rationale. Ask if N-terminal sequencing by Edman degradation or LC-MS confirmed complete and accurate cleavage in drug substance characterization.",
        ref:"ICH Q6B §3.2.S.3 | FDA Characterization Guidance for Therapeutic Proteins" },
      { id:"t01f", title:"Fc Engineering — CMC Implications",
        body:"Fc modifications change effector function, FcRn binding, or half-life and cascade throughout CMC: LALA (L234A/L235A) eliminates ADCC/CDC; YTE (M252Y/S254T/T256E) extends half-life 4-fold; afucosylation knock-in via FUT8 knockout enhances ADCC 50–100×. Each modification changes which attributes are CQAs, what potency assay format is needed, and what analytical characterization must be included.",
        why:"Fc engineering choices made at gene construction reverberate through the entire CMC program. An Fc-silent mAb doesn't need an ADCC potency assay; an afucosylated mAb requires fucosylation as a tightly controlled critical CQA.",
        how:"For each Fc modification in your program, list: (1) CQA it creates or eliminates, (2) required potency assay format, (3) analytical method added. Read Saunders Front Immunol 2019;10:1296.",
        ref:"ICH Q6B | FDA Potency Guidance (2008) | Saunders KO. Front Immunol 2019;10:1296" },
      { id:"t01g", title:"Gene Synthesis, Sequencing, and Variant Analysis",
        body:"After computational codon optimization, genes are synthesized by vendors (Twist, GeneArt, IDT) and fully confirmed by Sanger sequencing. During characterization, the expressed protein is analyzed by peptide mapping (LC-MS/MS) to confirm amino acid sequence and identify sequence variants. FDA guidance considers amino acid misincorporations at >0.1% reportable and requiring risk assessment.",
        why:"Sequence variants discovered after Phase 3 or in commercial manufacturing require immediate investigation, risk assessment, and potentially a Prior Approval Supplement. FDA has issued Warning Letters about inadequate sequence variant characterization.",
        how:"Read FDA 2015 workshop on sequence variant analysis by LC-MS. Ask your mentor: what detection threshold was used for sequence variant reporting in our characterization study?",
        ref:"ICH Q6B §3.2.S.3 | FDA Sequence Variant Analysis Workshop 2015 | ICH Q11 §3.2.S.2.2" },
    ],
    questions:[
      { id:"q01a", level:"Foundational", q:"What is codon optimization and why is it performed before expressing a recombinant biologic in CHO cells? What manufacturing consequences does poor codon choice create?", why:"Codon optimization is irreversible — it locks in your productivity ceiling.", how:"Read Gustafsson et al. 2004. Ask your mentor: what titer difference did optimization produce?", ref:"ICH Q11 §3.2.S.2.1 | ICH Q5B" },
      { id:"q01b", level:"Foundational", q:"What key genetic elements must an expression vector contain to drive stable, high-level expression in CHO cells, and why is each element a BLA-registered component?", why:"The vector is a permanent manufacturing raw material — cannot be changed post-IND without comparability data.", how:"Ask to see the vector map. Read ICH Q5B. Research GS vs DHFR selection.", ref:"ICH Q5B | ICH Q11" },
      { id:"q01c", level:"Intermediate", q:"What is a developability assessment and which in silico and biophysical tools identify CMC sequence liabilities before committing to CLD investment?", why:"Failing in developability is cheap. Failing after 2 years of CLD is catastrophic.", how:"Read Jarasch et al. 2015. Read Chennamsetty et al. on aggregation hotspot prediction.", ref:"ICH Q8 | FDA Characterization Guidance" },
      { id:"q01d", level:"Intermediate", q:"What is a QTPP and how does it cascade into CQA identification, analytical method selection, and specification setting?", why:"The QTPP anchors all CMC decisions. Regulators expect QTPP-driven thinking in BLA submissions.", how:"Read ICH Q8(R2). Study the A-Mab Case Study QTPP example.", ref:"ICH Q8(R2) | A-Mab Case Study" },
      { id:"q01e", level:"Advanced", q:"How does Fc engineering (LALA, YTE, afucosylation) affect CMC development strategy, the CQA list, and potency assay design?", why:"Fc engineering changes which attributes are CQAs and what potency assay format is required.", how:"Read Saunders 2019. Ask your mentor: what CMC challenges did Fc engineering create?", ref:"ICH Q6B | FDA Potency Guidance (2008)" },
    ]
  },
  { id:"s02", stage:"02", label:"Transfection & Integration", sub:"Stable Cell Lines", icon:"⚡", accent:"#F472B6",
    topics:[
      { id:"t02a", title:"Stable vs Transient Transfection",
        body:"Transient transfection (HEK293, ExpiCHO) delivers mg-scale material in 7–10 days without stable integration. Stable transfection permanently integrates the vector into the CHO genome via electroporation, followed by drug selection. Transient material enables early CQA profiling but lacks the cGMP documentation chain required for clinical dosing.",
        why:"Transient material cannot be used for Phase 1 dosing without a bridging comparability study. Programs that run late-stage characterization on transient material that differs from the eventual clinical cell line create costly analytical repetition.",
        how:"Ask your mentor: do we use transient material for any regulatory studies — what comparability was required? Draft a comparison: transient vs stable — timeline, yield, regulatory applicability.",
        ref:"FDA Phase 1 IND CMC Guidance (2014) | ICH Q11 | 21 CFR 312.23(a)(7)" },
      { id:"t02b", title:"Clonality Assurance — FDA 2021 Guidance",
        body:"FDA and EMA require imaging evidence that each production clone originated from a single cell. Accepted methods: limiting dilution with Poisson statistics (mean <0.5 cells/well), FACS single-cell deposition, or automated imaging (ClonePix2, Solentim VIPS). Two rounds of single-cell cloning are recommended. Day-0/1 images of each single-cell deposit must be archived as permanent cell line records.",
        why:"Non-clonal lines harbor subpopulations producing heterogeneous product. FDA has issued BLA Complete Response Letters specifically for inadequate clonality documentation. This requirement applies retroactively — missing imaging data cannot be reconstructed.",
        how:"Read FDA January 2021 Clonality Q&A document in full. Verify your program has day-0 imaging for each single-cell deposit. Ask your mentor: what imaging platform was used?",
        ref:"FDA 2021 Clonality Guidance Q&A | ICH Q5D Section B.3 | EMA Q&A on Cell Line Development" },
      { id:"t02c", title:"Selection System — GS vs DHFR",
        body:"Glutamine synthetase (GS) selection uses MSX to select for high-copy-number integrants in GS-knockout CHO cells, achieving stable pools in ~4 weeks. DHFR selection in DHFR-deficient CHO-DG44 uses methotrexate amplification (8+ weeks) to amplify gene copy up to 100–1,000 copies. GS has largely replaced DHFR due to faster timelines, better stability, and expired Lonza patents.",
        why:"Selection system choice affects timeline to stable pools, copy number distribution, genetic stability, and regulatory expectations. DHFR-amplified lines require additional gene copy number stability data over production PDLs.",
        how:"Ask your mentor which selection system was used. Research GS-knockout CHO (no MSX required) vs. DHFR-deficient CHO-DG44. Build a comparison table: GS vs DHFR — timeline, copy number, stability.",
        ref:"ICH Q5D | ICH Q5B | Cockett et al. Biotechnology 1990;8:662-7" },
      { id:"t02d", title:"Gene Copy Number and Zygosity Analysis",
        body:"Digital droplet PCR (ddPCR) or qPCR quantifies integrated transgene copies per genome equivalent. Copy number correlates with expression level but excessive copy number (>20) can indicate integration into repetitive elements with poor stability. High-copy clones in tandem repeats risk gene silencing over prolonged culture.",
        why:"Copy number data is increasingly expected in BLA packages when genetic stability questions arise or when explaining clone-to-clone productivity differences. It provides mechanistic insight into expression stability.",
        how:"Request ddPCR copy number data for lead clones. Ask: was there a copy number threshold used in clone selection? Read Zahn-Zabal et al. on CHO gene copy number and stability.",
        ref:"ICH Q5B | ICH Q5D | FDA Guidance on Expression Systems for Licensed Biologics" },
      { id:"t02e", title:"Integration Site Analysis by NGS",
        body:"NGS-based integration site analysis (inverse PCR + sequencing, or ODP-PCR) maps chromosomal location of transgene integration. Integration near telomeres, centromeres, or transcriptional silencing regions causes expression instability. Targeted integration using CRISPR/Cas9 at defined safe harbors is emerging but most commercial lines use random integration.",
        why:"FDA and EMA are increasingly requesting integration site data as part of cell substrate characterization in BLA packages, particularly for cell lines showing instability during genetic stability studies.",
        how:"Read Thomas et al. Biotech Bioeng 2018 on targeted integration. Check whether your organization has integration site data for the production cell line and understand when regulators would request it.",
        ref:"ICH Q5B | ICH Q5D | EMA Guideline on Cell Substrate Characterization (2019)" },
      { id:"t02f", title:"Epigenetic Silencing and Long-Term Expression Stability",
        body:"Transgene expression can be silenced over time via CpG methylation of the promoter or histone deacetylation at the integration locus. Silencing risk is highest when integration occurs in heterochromatin or near repetitive elements. Anti-silencing elements (matrix attachment regions, MARs; cHS4 insulators) can be included in vector design to improve long-term stability.",
        why:"Transgene silencing during commercial production — especially beyond EOP passage — constitutes a manufacturing failure. ICH Q5D genetic stability studies exist specifically to detect this risk before BLA filing.",
        how:"Review your program's genetic stability study at EOP + extended passage. Check for any downward trend in expression level or CQA shift across passages.",
        ref:"ICH Q5D Section B.4 | ICH Q5B | Recombinant DNA Advisory Committee guidelines" },
      { id:"t02g", title:"Backup Clone Strategy and Cell Line Archive",
        body:"Best practice requires selecting 2–3 backup clones from the CLD funnel alongside the lead clone. Backup clones should be banked at MCB stage before program advancement. Backup clone contingency plans address: lead clone genetic stability failure, contamination during the IND campaign, or unexpected product quality changes at scale. Switching clones after Phase 3 requires full ICH Q5E comparability data.",
        why:"Programs without backup clones have faced 2+ year delays after lead clone failures. Banking 2–3 backup MCBs (~$200K) is trivial vs. a program restart. FDA expects backup clone strategy documentation in the IND.",
        how:"Ask your mentor: do we have backup MCBs for our lead program? At what stage were they banked? Review your organization's cell line contingency plan.",
        ref:"ICH Q5D | FDA Phase 1 CMC Guidance | ISPE ATMP Manufacturing Guide (2019)" },
    ],
    questions:[
      { id:"q02a", level:"Foundational", q:"What is the difference between transient and stable transfection for biologic production, and when is each appropriate for CMC and regulatory purposes?", why:"Transient material lacks cGMP documentation for clinical dosing.", how:"Ask your mentor: do we use transient material — what comparability is required?", ref:"FDA Phase 1 CMC Guidance | ICH Q11" },
      { id:"q02b", level:"Intermediate", q:"What documentation is required to demonstrate clonality assurance, and why is imaging evidence a firm FDA expectation per the 2021 guidance?", why:"FDA has issued CRLs for inadequate clonality documentation.", how:"Read FDA 2021 clonality Q&A. Ask: what imaging platform do we use?", ref:"FDA 2021 Clonality Guidance | ICH Q5D" },
      { id:"q02c", level:"Advanced", q:"What is NGS-based integration site analysis and why are regulators increasingly requesting it in BLA packages?", why:"Integration into silenced chromatin causes expression loss; oncogene-adjacent integration is a theoretical safety concern.", how:"Read Thomas et al. 2018 on targeted integration in CHO.", ref:"ICH Q5B | ICH Q5D" },
    ]
  },
  { id:"s03", stage:"03", label:"Cell Line Development", sub:"Clone Selection", icon:"🔵", accent:"#38BDF8",
    topics:[
      { id:"t03a", title:"Clone Selection Criteria and the Selection Funnel",
        body:"Lead clone selection from hundreds of candidates uses a multi-criteria decision matrix balancing: specific productivity (qP), growth rate, metabolic profile (low lactate/ammonia production), product quality attributes (glycan profile, aggregation, charge variants), and genetic stability indicators. Typical funnel: ~500 clones → 48 deep well plate screen → 12 ambr15 → 4 shake flask → 2 bioreactor runs → 1 lead. Selection criteria should be pre-defined before screening begins.",
        why:"Clone selection is the most consequential CMC decision — the selected clone defines manufacturing economics and product quality for the entire lifecycle. A clone with suboptimal glycosylation or high aggregation tendency creates problems no downstream process can fully correct.",
        how:"Ask to see your program's clone funnel data. Ask your mentor: was there a higher-titer clone rejected for quality reasons? Draft a clone selection scorecard with weighted criteria.",
        ref:"ICH Q5D | ICH Q11 | Walsh G. Nat Biotechnol 2018;36:1136-45" },
      { id:"t03b", title:"Genetic Stability Testing per ICH Q5D",
        body:"ICH Q5D requires demonstrating stable productivity and product quality over the full manufacturing duration in population doublings (PDLs). Testing at MCB, WCB, End-of-Production (EOP), and Extended Limit passage. Attributes monitored: expression level, key CQAs (glycosylation, purity, potency), and sequence integrity by PCR. EOP is defined as the commercial-scale production duration + safety margin.",
        why:"Genetic instability discovered post-BLA means potentially having a different product mid-lifecycle. Missing EOP genetic stability data is a CRL-triggering deficiency. It is also an irreversible time-dependent study — missing timepoints cannot be retrospectively obtained.",
        how:"Read ICH Q5D Section B.4. Build a stability testing matrix showing all PDL timepoints and attributes. Ask your mentor: is our EOP passage number confirmed for the commercial bioreactor run duration?",
        ref:"ICH Q5D | ICH Q5B | 21 CFR 610.18" },
      { id:"t03c", title:"Product Quality Attribute Profiling During CLD",
        body:"CQA profiling during clone selection uses small-scale purified material (typically Protein A spin columns from ambr15 or shake flask culture) to assess: glycan profile (main species — G0F/G1F/G2F; high mannose; afucosylation), aggregation by SEC-HPLC, charge variants by icIEF, and purity by CE-SDS. Clone-to-clone quality differences can be substantial — selecting on titer alone risks advancing a clone with unfavorable quality.",
        why:"Clone selection decisions made in CLD are largely irreversible post-IND. A clone with high Man5 glycan content or elevated aggregation propensity requires formulation and process accommodations that constrain all future CMC decisions.",
        how:"Ask to see CQA profiling data from the clone selection campaign. Review the clone scoring matrix: what weight did each CQA receive? Was any clone rejected despite having the highest titer?",
        ref:"ICH Q6B | ICH Q5D | ICH Q8(R2) | A-Mab Case Study" },
      { id:"t03d", title:"Specific Productivity (qP) and Integrated Titer Measurement",
        body:"Specific productivity (qP, in pg/cell/day) measures the amount of product secreted per cell per day and is the fundamental measure of cell productivity independent of growth rate. Integrated viable cell concentration (IVCC) combined with qP gives the final titer. qP is measured by dividing final titer by IVCC using trapezoidal integration. A typical high-producing CHO clone achieves qP of 40–80 pg/cell/day.",
        why:"qP is the productivity metric that enables comparing clones at different growth rates. Understanding qP vs. growth rate trade-offs shapes feeding strategy and media design. High qP at sustainable viability gives the best titer at commercial scale.",
        how:"Read Dietmair et al. on qP measurement methodology. For your program's lead clone, calculate qP from the fed-batch time-course data using trapezoidal IVCC integration.",
        ref:"ICH Q11 | FDA Process Development Guidance | Dietmair et al. Biotech Bioeng 2010;107:116" },
      { id:"t03e", title:"Metabolic Profiling — Lactate, Ammonia, Glucose",
        body:"Metabolic profiling during CLD monitors: glucose consumption rate, lactate production (indicator of metabolic efficiency — lactate switch from production to consumption is a sign of productive culture), ammonia accumulation (inhibits growth and can shift glycosylation), and amino acid depletion profiles. Clones with efficient glucose metabolism (low lactate/glucose ratio) perform better at commercial scale where metabolic byproduct accumulation is amplified.",
        why:"Poor metabolic efficiency causes osmolality spikes (from ammonia/lactate accumulation), growth inhibition, and glycosylation shifts that are challenging CPPs to control at scale. Selecting metabolically efficient clones avoids these downstream complications.",
        how:"Plot lactate concentration and lactate/glucose ratio over time for your clone candidates. Identify whether a 'lactate switch' (reversal from production to consumption) occurs mid-culture — a sign of good metabolic efficiency.",
        ref:"ICH Q11 | Luo et al. Biotechnol Bioeng 2012;109:146-56" },
      { id:"t03f", title:"HCP Profile and Immunogenicity Risk Across Clones",
        body:"Different CHO clones produce different Host Cell Protein (HCP) repertoires at different abundances. Some HCPs — particularly PLBL2 (a lipase that degrades polysorbate), cathepsins, and lipoprotein lipase — are high-risk due to immunogenicity or product stability impact. LC-MS-based HCP profiling during CLD can identify clones with unfavorable HCP profiles before advancing to scale.",
        why:"HCP ELISA coverage is antibody-dependent — clones with high levels of poorly immunogenic HCPs may appear clean on ELISA but carry hidden risk. Selecting for HCP profile at CLD stage avoids late-stage safety concerns.",
        how:"Ask your CMC team: was LC-MS HCP profiling done during clone selection? Read Labrenz 2014 on PLBL2. Ask if PLBL2 abundance was assessed across candidate clones.",
        ref:"ICH Q6B | FDA HCP Guidance | Labrenz SR. J Pharm Sci 2014;103:1298-310" },
      { id:"t03g", title:"Clone Fingerprinting, Identity, and Contamination Control",
        body:"Each production clone must be authenticated by short tandem repeat (STR) profiling to create a unique DNA fingerprint. This fingerprint is archived and used to confirm the identity of the MCB and each WCB. STR profiling also detects cross-contamination between cell lines in a multi-product facility. Mycoplasma testing at each banking passage and before any manufacturing campaign is mandatory.",
        why:"Clone mix-ups in multi-product facilities have caused commercial lot contaminations. STR profiling is the definitive identity test required by ICH Q5D and FDA for all cell bank characterization packages.",
        how:"Ask your mentor: was STR profiling performed for our lead clone? Where is the reference STR profile archived? Read ICH Q5D Section B.5 on cell identity testing requirements.",
        ref:"ICH Q5D §B.5 | ATCC STR profiling guidance | 21 CFR 610.18" },
    ],
    questions:[
      { id:"q03a", level:"Foundational", q:"What criteria drive lead production clone selection and how do you balance titer against product quality attributes when they conflict?", why:"Clone selection defines everything downstream forever — a high-titer clone with poor quality creates unfixable problems.", how:"Ask to see the clone funnel data. Ask if a higher-titer clone was rejected for quality reasons.", ref:"ICH Q5D | ICH Q11" },
      { id:"q03b", level:"Foundational", q:"What is specific productivity (qP), how is it measured in fed-batch culture, and how does the qP vs. growth rate trade-off shape media and feeding strategy?", why:"qP is the fundamental productivity metric enabling comparison of clones at different growth rates.", how:"Read Dietmair et al. on qP measurement. Ask your mentor: what qP threshold advanced clones?", ref:"ICH Q11 | FDA Process Development Guidance" },
      { id:"q03c", level:"Intermediate", q:"What does ICH Q5D require for genetic stability testing, how many PDLs must be covered, and what quality attributes must be monitored at end-of-production?", why:"Missing EOP data is a BLA deficiency that can trigger a CRL.", how:"Read ICH Q5D Section B.4. Build a stability test matrix.", ref:"ICH Q5D | ICH Q5B" },
    ]
  },
  { id:"s04", stage:"04", label:"Cell Banking", sub:"MCB / WCB", icon:"🏦", accent:"#34D399",
    topics:[
      { id:"t04a", title:"Two-Tier MCB/WCB Banking System",
        body:"The Master Cell Bank (MCB) is derived from the selected lead clone — 100–500 vials cryopreserved at passage P+3 to P+7 in controlled-rate freezers. The MCB is prepared once and serves as the permanent source for all Working Cell Banks (WCBs) throughout the product lifecycle. WCBs are prepared from single MCB vials, typically 50–200 vials each. Multiple geographic storage sites (minimum 2) provide redundancy against catastrophic loss.",
        why:"The MCB is irreplaceable — contamination or storage failure threatens the entire program. Every batch ever manufactured originates from the MCB. FDA considers the MCB a critical manufacturing material requiring documented qualification, testing, and storage controls.",
        how:"Read ICH Q5D Section A for the full two-tier rationale. Ask your mentor: how many MCB vials exist, in how many locations, and what is the cold chain monitoring program?",
        ref:"ICH Q5D | 21 CFR 610.18 | EMA Guidelines on Cell Substrates" },
      { id:"t04b", title:"Cell Bank Testing — IND vs BLA Requirements",
        body:"Phase 1 IND MCB testing (minimum): sterility (USP <71>), mycoplasma (USP <63>), in vitro adventitious agents, identity (STR or isoenzyme). BLA MCB testing (full ICH Q5D panel): adds in vivo adventitious agents, retroviruses (S+L- assay, PERT), species-specific viral agents (e.g., CHO virus — REV-1), karyology, and tumorigenicity. WCB requires abbreviated testing vs MCB.",
        why:"Understanding the testing escalation from IND to BLA prevents last-minute BLA delays. MCB viral safety testing timelines (6–12 months for full panel) must be planned into the program Gantt chart, not discovered at submission.",
        how:"Build a two-column table: MCB tests required at IND vs BLA, with ICH Q5D section references for each. Ask your mentor: are all MCB tests complete for our BLA timeline?",
        ref:"ICH Q5D | ICH Q5A(R1) | FDA Phase 1 CMC Guidance | 21 CFR 610.18" },
      { id:"t04c", title:"Adventitious Agent Testing per ICH Q5A(R1)",
        body:"ICH Q5A(R1) mandates testing for adventitious viral agents in cell banks and during manufacturing. Cell bank viral testing methods: in vitro assays (MRC-5, Vero, MEF cells), in vivo rodent and embryonated egg assays, reverse transcriptase assay (PERT) for retroviruses, TEM for retroviral particles, and species-specific assays (e.g., CHO-specific Reovirus-like agent). Manufacturing: bioburden testing and viral clearance validation complete the viral safety matrix.",
        why:"Adventitious viral contamination of a biologic product is a life-threatening safety event. The 2009 Genzyme Cerezyme contamination (Vesivirus 2117) caused a global shortage affecting 6,000 patients. ICH Q5A testing is the primary prevention layer.",
        how:"Read ICH Q5A(R1) Section 4 and Table 1 for the full testing matrix. Ask your CMC team: where are we in the full adventitious agent testing program — is in vivo testing complete?",
        ref:"ICH Q5A(R1) | WHO TRS 926 Annex 3 | FDA Points to Consider on Viral Safety" },
      { id:"t04d", title:"Cryopreservation Conditions, Viability, and Recovery",
        body:"Standard cryopreservation medium for CHO: 10% DMSO in basal media or serum, with controlled-rate freezing (−1°C/min) to −80°C before transfer to liquid nitrogen vapor phase (−140°C or below). Viability post-thaw should be ≥80% (by trypan blue exclusion) before advancing. Recovery slope (time to reach target VCD) is monitored as a quality indicator. Each MCB vial is qualified by testing 1–3 representative vials for viability and recovery.",
        why:"Poor cryopreservation protocol causes low post-thaw viability, slow growth kinetics, and potential product quality differences vs the development cell line. A vial with <70% post-thaw viability from an MCB that cannot be recovered is a manufacturing disruption.",
        how:"Review your site's SOP for MCB preparation and post-thaw qualification. Ask: what post-thaw viability acceptance criterion is used? Was controlled-rate freezing validated?",
        ref:"ICH Q5D | PDA TR-26 Cell Banking Guideline | USP <1045>" },
      { id:"t04e", title:"Cell Bank Storage Redundancy and Chain-of-Custody",
        body:"Best practice: MCB split across 3 independent storage locations — primary manufacturing site, off-site long-term archive (liquid nitrogen), and a second off-site backup (different geographic region). WCBs also require minimum 2-site storage. Each vial location is tracked in a validated inventory management system. Annual temperature monitoring and alarm system qualification are required. Chain-of-custody documentation covers every vial removal.",
        why:"Single-site storage has resulted in catastrophic cell bank losses from facility failures. The Genzyme contamination (2009) was in part caused by inadequate redundancy. FDA inspectors verify that cell bank storage controls meet expectations — failures generate 483 observations.",
        how:"Ask your mentor: how many storage locations does our MCB have? Is the inventory management system validated? Review the most recent alarm system qualification record.",
        ref:"ICH Q5D | 21 CFR 211.68 | FDA Guidance on Cell Substrates" },
      { id:"t04f", title:"Mycoplasma Testing — USP <63> and Rapid Methods",
        body:"Mycoplasma testing is required for all cell banks and pre-harvest bulk. USP <63> / EP 2.6.7 culture-based method requires 28 days. Rapid qPCR-based methods (e.g., MycoAlert Luminescence assay, MycoSensor qPCR) are validated as complements. Testing must be performed on each MCB and WCB lot, each cell culture harvest, and any unscheduled material used in process characterization. A mycoplasma-positive cell bank is deemed a critical failure requiring destruction.",
        why:"Mycoplasma contamination in a bioreactor is not detectable by routine in-process testing, grows undetected for weeks, and can affect CQAs (glycosylation shifts, metabolic changes) before causing cell death. A post-approval mycoplasma detection triggers a Class I recall.",
        how:"Review your manufacturing facility's mycoplasma testing program. Ask: do we use rapid testing as a complement or replacement for culture? Read USP <63> for the full method requirements.",
        ref:"USP <63> | EP 2.6.7 | ICH Q5A(R1) | 21 CFR 610.12" },
      { id:"t04g", title:"Passage Number Control and In-Process Cell Culture Monitoring",
        body:"Passage number must be tightly controlled from MCB thaw to EOP (end of production). The cumulative PDL or passage number at EOP is defined during development and must not be exceeded in commercial manufacturing without re-qualifying the genetic stability data. In-process controls during production culture include daily VCD, viability, glucose, lactate, and pH monitoring — deviations from defined IPCs trigger investigation per the batch record.",
        why:"Exceeding the EOP passage number in a commercial batch is a regulatory filing issue — the batch disposition is uncertain because it falls outside the validated process space. Rigorous passage tracking prevents this.",
        how:"Review the commercial batch record for a representative production run. Check that the cumulative passage number from MCB thaw is documented and within the qualified EOP limit.",
        ref:"ICH Q5D | ICH Q11 | FDA Process Validation Guidance (2011)" },
    ],
    questions:[
      { id:"q04a", level:"Foundational", q:"What is the MCB/WCB two-tiered cell banking system and what is the regulatory rationale for maintaining this hierarchy?", why:"Every batch ever manufactured originates from the MCB — if lost without backup, the entire program is at risk.", how:"Read ICH Q5D Section A. Ask your mentor: how many MCB vials are stored and in how many locations?", ref:"ICH Q5D | 21 CFR 610.18" },
      { id:"q04b", level:"Intermediate", q:"What testing must be performed on the MCB before Phase 1 IND vs. BLA submission? How do these timelines affect program planning?", why:"MCB viral safety testing takes 6–12 months — must be planned into the BLA Gantt, not discovered at submission.", how:"Build a two-column table: MCB tests at IND vs BLA. Use ICH Q5D as primary reference.", ref:"ICH Q5D | ICH Q5A(R1) | FDA Phase 1 CMC Guidance" },
    ]
  },
  { id:"s05", stage:"05", label:"Upstream Development", sub:"Bioreactor Process", icon:"🔬", accent:"#22D3EE",
    topics:[
      { id:"t05a", title:"CPPs, Glycosylation Control, and Media Supplementation",
        body:"Key upstream CPP candidates: pH (6.8–7.2 range for CHO), dissolved oxygen (30–50% saturation), temperature (shift from 37°C to 31–34°C to boost qP), osmolality (280–350 mOsm/kg), CO2 accumulation, agitation rate. Glycosylation is controlled through media: manganese activates β1,4-galactosyltransferase (↑galactosylation), galactose supplementation increases G1F/G2F content, copper depletion reduces fucosylation (↑ADCC), and ammonia accumulation disrupts Golgi pH causing aberrant glycosylation.",
        why:"CPP identification is a regulatory commitment filed in the BLA. Missing a CPP means it may drift uncontrolled commercially, causing batch CQA failures. These process-glycan relationships must be characterized and mechanistically understood.",
        how:"Build a table: each CPP → CQA impact → mechanistic explanation. Ask your mentor: which parameter had the most unexpected CQA impact in your process characterization DoE?",
        ref:"ICH Q8 | ICH Q11 | FDA Process Validation Guidance (2011)" },
      { id:"t05b", title:"Scale-Down Model Qualification",
        body:"A qualified scale-down model (SDM) at 2–15L must demonstrate representativeness of the commercial-scale bioreactor (1,000–20,000L). Qualification parameters: side-by-side CQA comparison (≥3 lots each scale), matched kLa (oxygen transfer coefficient), mixing time, pCO2 profile, osmolality, and temperature control. All process characterization DoEs run in the qualified SDM. Regulatory submissions reference SDM qualification data as the scientific basis for commercial-scale prediction.",
        why:"The SDM is the foundation of all process characterization data. An unqualified SDM invalidates the entire process characterization package — the worst discovery to make 6 months before BLA filing.",
        how:"Read Hsu et al. on SDM qualification criteria. Ask your mentor: has FDA ever challenged our SDM representativeness? Review the SDM qualification report key acceptance criteria.",
        ref:"ICH Q11 | FDA Process Validation Guidance (2011) | ASTM E2935" },
      { id:"t05c", title:"Fed-Batch vs. Perfusion Process Selection",
        body:"Fed-batch (bolus or continuous feeding) remains the dominant commercial mAb platform, achieving 3–15 g/L titers in 12–18 days. Perfusion (continuous media exchange via ATF or TFF) maintains VCD >50×10⁶ cells/mL at steady state, enabling intensified production. Continuous perfusion is growing for high-demand molecules and Cytiva/Sartorius 500L perfusion bioreactors are commercially deployed. Each mode has distinct CPP sets and process characterization requirements.",
        why:"Process mode selection is a BLA-filed manufacturing decision that affects facility footprint, COGS, and regulatory complexity. Switching from fed-batch to perfusion post-approval requires a full Prior Approval Supplement with comparability data.",
        how:"Read Walther et al. Biotechnol J 2019 on perfusion vs fed-batch economics. Ask your mentor: was perfusion evaluated for our process — what drove the selection?",
        ref:"ICH Q11 | FDA Process Validation Guidance | Walther et al. Biotechnol J 2019;14:e1700706" },
      { id:"t05d", title:"Media Development and Raw Material Control",
        body:"Chemically defined media (CDM) have replaced serum-containing media in commercial biologics. CDM formulations (50–100 components) are optimized for titer, cell growth, and quality attributes. Raw material lot-to-lot variability — particularly for hydrolysates, lipid mixtures, and recombinant growth factors — can affect glycosylation and titer. Critical raw materials (CRMs) require vendor qualification, lot release testing, and justified substitution procedures.",
        why:"A raw material change without appropriate qualification is a regulatory violation (21 CFR 211.80). Undetected raw material variation has caused batch failures where the root cause took months to identify. CRM variation is a top cause of CPV signals in commercial manufacturing.",
        how:"Ask your mentor: what are the CRMs for the bioreactor step? What lot release tests are performed? Has any raw material variation caused a batch quality issue?",
        ref:"ICH Q11 | ICH Q7 | 21 CFR 211.80 | FDA Raw Materials Guidance" },
      { id:"t05e", title:"CO2 Accumulation and pH/Osmolality Impact at Scale",
        body:"pCO2 accumulation is a major scale-up challenge. At 10,000–20,000L scale, CO2 stripping efficiency (kLa for CO2) decreases dramatically vs. small scale. Elevated pCO2 (>150 mmHg) inhibits growth, shifts intracellular pH, and increases osmolality from bicarbonate accumulation — compounding with NaOH base additions for pH control. Strategies to control pCO2: increased sparging flow, reduced aeration pressure, and lower bicarbonate concentration in the medium.",
        why:"Programs that don't characterize pCO2 as a CPP candidate at scale may find batch-to-batch CQA variation at commercial scale that is traceable to CO2 differences driven by bioreactor fill volume changes or agitation variations.",
        how:"Read Mostafa & Gu 2003 (Biotechnol Bioeng 86:539) on pCO2 effects. Ask your mentor: is pCO2 a CPP in our process, and how is it controlled at commercial scale?",
        ref:"ICH Q8 | ICH Q11 | Mostafa & Gu Biotechnol Bioeng 2003;86:539-50" },
      { id:"t05f", title:"Temperature Shift Strategy for Productivity and Quality",
        body:"Temperature shifts (from 37°C to 30–34°C mid-culture) are widely used to increase qP and extend culture duration in fed-batch CHO processes. The mechanism: reduced metabolic rate at lower temperature → lower glucose consumption → reduced lactate and ammonia → extended high-viability culture. Temperature shift timing and magnitude are CPP candidates because they affect glycosylation (lower temperature → higher galactosylation, reduced sialylation in CHO).",
        why:"Temperature shift timing is a common CPP because small deviations in shift timing or target temperature reliably produce measurable CQA changes. It is one of the most useful examples for explaining CPP-CQA relationships in regulatory submissions.",
        how:"For your process, identify: shift time point, shift temperature, and CQA response to shift ±1°C and ±2h timing. Ask your mentor: was temperature shift characterized in the process DoE?",
        ref:"ICH Q8 | ICH Q11 | Kaufmann et al. Biotechnol Bioeng 1999;63:573-82" },
      { id:"t05g", title:"In-Process Controls (IPCs) and Sampling Strategy",
        body:"Upstream IPCs performed daily during production culture: viable cell density (VCD), cell viability (% viable), glucose concentration, lactate, pH (vs. target), dissolved oxygen, and osmolality. IPCs are not release tests — they are in-process monitoring checks with action limits that trigger process adjustments or deviations. IPC sampling strategy (time, volume, method) must be documented in the batch record and qualified for representativeness.",
        why:"IPCs are the operator's primary manufacturing control tool. Missing or poorly documented IPC data is a cGMP deficiency. Action limits define when a deviation must be initiated — having well-defined action limits prevents both over-investigation and under-investigation.",
        how:"Review a recent batch record for the bioreactor step. Identify each IPC, its action limit, and any deviations that were initiated. Read 21 CFR 211.111 on in-process sampling requirements.",
        ref:"ICH Q11 | FDA Process Validation Guidance (2011) | 21 CFR 211.111" },
      { id:"t05h", title:"PAT — Process Analytical Technology",
        body:"PAT (ICH Q8 definition) uses real-time monitoring tools to provide timely measurements of critical quality and performance attributes during manufacturing. Upstream PAT examples: near-IR probes for real-time glucose/lactate measurement, Raman spectroscopy for metabolite monitoring, capacitance probes for VCD estimation, and online dissolved CO2 sensors. PAT enables real-time feedback control (closed-loop pH, DO) reducing process variability.",
        why:"FDA's 2004 PAT Guidance encourages PAT adoption as a means to reduce process variability and support continuous manufacturing. Companies implementing PAT see reduced OOS rates and improved CPV data quality. PAT data can support real-time release testing (RTRT) applications.",
        how:"Read FDA PAT Guidance (2004). Ask your mentor: what PAT tools are deployed on our bioreactor — is any data used for real-time process control or release testing support?",
        ref:"FDA PAT Guidance (2004) | ICH Q8(R2) | ICH Q10" },
    ],
    questions:[
      { id:"q05a", level:"Foundational", q:"What are the key bioreactor CPPs in fed-batch CHO culture? Give the mechanistic basis for at least three CPP–CQA relationships.", why:"CPP identification requires mechanistic understanding — required for characterization design and CPP classification in the BLA.", how:"Build a table: parameter → CQA impact → mechanism.", ref:"ICH Q8 | ICH Q11 | FDA Process Validation Guidance" },
      { id:"q05b", level:"Intermediate", q:"How does media composition — manganese, galactose, and ammonia — mechanistically control mAb glycosylation and how is this built into the upstream control strategy?", why:"These are direct process levers for glycan CQAs.", how:"Read Konrad et al. on manganese and galactosylation. Ask your mentor: is manganese a CPP?", ref:"ICH Q8 | ICH Q6B" },
      { id:"q05c", level:"Advanced", q:"How do you design a full DoE for bioreactor process characterization to distinguish CPPs from KPPs from non-key parameters?", why:"Under-powered designs miss CPPs; classification output is a regulatory commitment.", how:"Read Box, Hunter & Hunter Chapter 3. Ask your mentor: what effect size did we power our DoE to detect?", ref:"ICH Q8 | ICH Q9 | ICH Q11" },
      { id:"q05d", level:"Expert", q:"Upstream optimization improves titer 40% but shifts glycosylation outside historical comparability ranges. What is your full CMC and regulatory strategy?", why:"This is a classic CMC leadership dilemma — titer gain vs. CQA change.", how:"Read ICH Q5E. Build a decision tree: what tests first, regulatory filing pathway.", ref:"ICH Q5E | ICH Q8 | FDA Comparability Guidance (2003)" },
    ]
  },
  { id:"s06", stage:"06", label:"Downstream Development", sub:"Purification Train", icon:"⚗️", accent:"#4ADE80",
    topics:[
      { id:"t06a", title:"Standard mAb Purification Train",
        body:"Platform mAb downstream process: (1) Harvest clarification — centrifugation + depth filtration to remove cells and debris; (2) Protein A capture chromatography — selective IgG capture, pH 7→3 elution; (3) Low pH viral inactivation (pH 3.4–3.7, ≥60 min hold) — enveloped virus clearance step; (4) Polishing — CEX for aggregate/HCP/charge variant removal, AEX in flow-through mode for DNA/virus/endotoxin; (5) Viral filtration (20 nm Planova/Viresolve) — non-enveloped virus clearance; (6) UF/DF — concentration to target and buffer exchange to formulation buffer.",
        why:"This sequence is conserved across ~80% of commercial mAb processes. CMC leaders must explain every step's rationale fluently — required in regulatory meetings, facility inspections, and technical transfer discussions.",
        how:"Draw the complete flow diagram labeling each step's CQA impact, CPPs, and the class of impurity removed. Read Shukla et al. J Chromatogr B 2007;848:28.",
        ref:"ICH Q11 | ICH Q5A(R1) | ICH Q6B | Shukla et al. J Chromatogr B 2007;848:28-39" },
      { id:"t06b", title:"HCP Clearance and PLBL2 Risk",
        body:"Host cell proteins monitored by ELISA (primary — multi-analyte) and LC-MS/MS (orthogonal — single-analyte identification). ELISA coverage depends on rabbit immunogenicity to CHO HCPs — high-risk HCPs like PLBL2 (phospholipase B-like 2, a lipase that degrades PS80), cathepsins B/D/L, and lipoprotein lipase may not be detected by generic CHO HCP ELISA kits if not well-represented in the immunogen.",
        why:"PLBL2-mediated PS80 degradation in commercial products caused visible particle formation and FDA-initiated recalls. PLBL2 is not well detected by many commercial HCP ELISA kits. FDA scrutinizes HCP ELISA coverage and HCP clearance strategy in every BLA review.",
        how:"Read Labrenz 2014 on PLBL2 (J Pharm Sci 103:1298). Read Singer et al. 2021. Ask your mentor: do we specifically monitor PLBL2 by LC-MS? What is our ELISA coverage?",
        ref:"ICH Q6B | FDA HCP Guidance | Labrenz SR. J Pharm Sci 2014;103:1298-310" },
      { id:"t06c", title:"Viral Clearance Validation per ICH Q5A(R1)",
        body:"Viral clearance validation demonstrates that the downstream process provides adequate virus removal/inactivation across two orthogonal mechanisms. ICH Q5A(R1) requires testing 4 model viruses representing different morphologies/sizes: a large enveloped (MuLV), large non-enveloped (reoV-3), small non-enveloped (parvovirus B19/MVM), and an additional site-specific virus. Steps typically contributing: low pH VI (≥4 logs for enveloped viruses), Protein A (limited), polishing CEX (limited), viral filtration (≥4 logs, especially for small non-enveloped).",
        why:"Viral safety of biologics derived from mammalian cells is a critical patient safety requirement. Viral clearance data is scrutinized in every BLA. A pH excursion outside the validated VI hold range is a potential viral safety event triggering regulatory reporting per 21 CFR 312.32.",
        how:"Read ICH Q5A(R1) Section 4 for the full validation framework. Ask your mentor: what is our log reduction factor (LRF) for MVM viral filtration? What is the validated pH range for low pH VI?",
        ref:"ICH Q5A(R1) | WHO TRS 926 Annex 4 | 21 CFR 312.32" },
      { id:"t06d", title:"Protein A Resin Lifetime and Reuse Justification",
        body:"Protein A resin (MabSelect, MabSelect SuRe, Praesto, CaptivA) costs $5,000–15,000/L and is used 100–200 cycles commercially. Reuse lifetime studies demonstrate consistent performance across claimed cycles: HCP clearance, DNA clearance, aggregate clearance, yield, eluate pool CQAs, and leachate (protein A ligand) levels. Cycle lifetime studies at scale-down must replicate commercial-scale loading conditions (g/L resin loading challenge).",
        why:"Protein A resin reuse is a major BLA topic — FDA inspectors examine resin lifetime data in detail. Inadequate lifetime studies mean claiming more reuse cycles than validated, a cGMP violation. Economic pressure to maximize reuse must be balanced with demonstrated safety.",
        how:"Review your Protein A resin lifetime validation report. Ask your mentor: how many cycles are qualified, what CQA served as the lifetime-limiting criterion, and what safety margin was built in?",
        ref:"ICH Q11 | ICH Q6B | Cytiva MabSelect Platform Guidance | FDA Process Validation Guidance" },
      { id:"t06e", title:"Aggregate Removal — CEX, AEX, and HIC Polishing",
        body:"Polishing chromatography removes residual aggregates, charge variants, and HCPs after Protein A capture. CEX (Capto SP, Fractogel SE Hi-Cap) binds mAb under low-conductivity conditions — aggregates and acidic variants often bind more tightly or wash off earlier. AEX in flow-through mode (Capto Q, Mustang Q) removes DNA, endotoxin, and viruses without binding the mAb. HIC (Capto Phenyl, Butyl) removes hydrophobic aggregates and some HCPs. Step sequencing and buffer conditions are critical CPPs.",
        why:"Aggregation is typically the first CQA to approach specification limits in stability studies. Inadequate aggregate clearance in the purification process increases the risk of immunogenicity and requires tighter formulation and stability controls.",
        how:"For your downstream process, map each polishing step to the impurity it primarily removes. Ask your mentor: was a HIC polishing step evaluated — what drove the decision to include or exclude it?",
        ref:"ICH Q11 | ICH Q6B | GE Healthcare mAb purification handbook" },
      { id:"t06f", title:"UF/DF — Concentration and Buffer Exchange",
        body:"Ultrafiltration/diafiltration (UF/DF) using 10–30 kDa MWCO PES or cellulose membranes concentrates the mAb to the target DS concentration (typically 10–200 mg/mL) and exchanges the buffer to formulation buffer composition. Key parameters: transmembrane pressure (TMP), cross-flow rate, concentration factor, diafiltration volumes (typically 7–10 DV for >99.9% buffer exchange). Membrane reuse (if applicable) requires lifetime validation.",
        why:"UF/DF is the final step before formulation and fill. Concentration-dependent aggregation and viscosity challenges emerge here — particularly for high-concentration mAb products (>100 mg/mL). These issues must be resolved in process development, not post-BLA.",
        how:"Review your DS UF/DF development report. Ask: what concentration was targeted, was there a concentration-dependent aggregation or viscosity issue, and how was it resolved?",
        ref:"ICH Q11 | USP <1231> | FDA Process Validation Guidance" },
      { id:"t06g", title:"Endotoxin Control Strategy Throughout DSP",
        body:"Endotoxin (lipopolysaccharide from gram-negative bacteria) must be controlled throughout the downstream process. Primary control points: raw material endotoxin testing (water for injection must meet USP <85>/EP 2.6.14 specifications), sanitization of equipment and columns with NaOH (0.1–1 M), and use of depyrogenated containers. Release testing of DS: Limulus amebocyte lysate (LAL, kinetic turbidimetric or kinetic chromogenic) per USP <85>. Endotoxin acceptance limits for parenterals: <5 EU/mL (IV) or <0.5 EU/mg protein.",
        why:"Endotoxin contamination in an injectable biologic causes pyrogenic reactions potentially leading to septic shock. An endotoxin OOS is a Class I recall scenario. Systematic endotoxin control from media prep through fill-finish is more effective than relying solely on release testing.",
        how:"Map each downstream step and identify the endotoxin control measure (sanitization, testing, depyrogenation). Ask your mentor: what is the endotoxin acceptance limit for our DS, and is it clinically justified?",
        ref:"USP <85> | EP 2.6.14 | ICH Q6B | 21 CFR 610.13(b)" },
      { id:"t06h", title:"Leachables from DSP Unit Operations",
        body:"Downstream chromatography resins and membrane devices can leach small molecules into the product stream. Key leachables: Protein A ligand (from MabSelect — limit typically ≤2 ng/mg), resin ligands (dye-based — e.g., Blue Sepharose), plasticizers and antioxidants from tubing and membranes, and metal ions from stainless steel at low pH. Leachables must be identified, quantified, and assessed against ICH Q3E or ICH M7 thresholds.",
        why:"Protein A leaching is routinely challenged in BLA reviews. Plasticizer leachables (DEHP, Irganox) from silicone tubing and single-use components are increasingly scrutinized as potential impurities. Uncontrolled leachables can affect product stability or patient safety.",
        how:"Review your DS process-related impurity panel. Ask: which leachables are tested at release, what are the acceptance limits, and how were they justified?",
        ref:"ICH Q3E | ICH M7 | BPOG Leachables Risk Assessment Guidance | FDA Guidance on Single-Use Systems" },
    ],
    questions:[
      { id:"q06a", level:"Foundational", q:"What is the standard downstream purification train for a mAb and what is the scientific rationale for each step?", why:"Every CMC professional must explain each step's rationale fluently — asked in every CMC interview, regulatory meeting, and inspection.", how:"Draw the complete flow diagram. Label each step with purpose, CPPs, and CQA impact.", ref:"ICH Q11 | ICH Q5A(R1) | ICH Q6B" },
      { id:"q06b", level:"Foundational", q:"What are HCPs and why are they a critical quality attribute? What are the specific limitations of HCP ELISA that require complementary LC-MS analysis?", why:"HCPs can be immunogenic and have caused recalls (PLBL2).", how:"Read Singer et al. 2021. Ask: what is our ELISA coverage?", ref:"ICH Q6B | FDA HCP Guidance" },
      { id:"q06c", level:"Intermediate", q:"What is low pH viral inactivation, what model viruses validate it per ICH Q5A, and what manufacturing excursion constitutes a viral safety concern?", why:"A pH excursion above the upper validated limit is a potential viral safety event.", how:"Read ICH Q5A(R1) Section 4. Ask: what LRF was achieved in our VI validation?", ref:"ICH Q5A(R1) | FDA Points to Consider | 21 CFR 312.32" },
      { id:"q06d", level:"Advanced", q:"How do you justify Protein A resin reuse in a BLA and what cycle lifetime studies demonstrate consistent HCP clearance across claimed cycles?", why:"Protein A costs $5,000–15,000/L. Reuse justification has major quality and COGS implications.", how:"Review your Protein A resin lifetime validation report. Ask: how many cycles do we qualify?", ref:"ICH Q11 | ICH Q6B | Cytiva MabSelect Guidance" },
      { id:"q06e", level:"Expert", q:"Post-approval, you discover a polishing step is not clearing PLBL2, which is degrading PS80. What are your simultaneous CMC, analytical, and regulatory actions?", why:"Post-approval HCP safety discoveries require parallel analytical work, process modification, and regulatory filing under time pressure.", how:"Read Labrenz 2014. Read FDA post-approval guidance.", ref:"ICH Q12 | FDA Post-Approval Guidance | ICH Q5E" },
    ]
  },
  { id:"s07", stage:"07", label:"Analytical Development", sub:"Methods & CQAs", icon:"📊", accent:"#A78BFA",
    topics:[
      { id:"t07a", title:"CQA Risk Assessment and the FMEA-Based Approach",
        body:"CQA identification uses FMEA-based risk assessment scoring each quality attribute on severity (impact on safety/efficacy), occurrence (frequency of observation), and detectability (ability to monitor). High-risk attributes become CQAs requiring controlled specifications. ICH Q8(R2) defines a CQA as 'a physical, chemical, biological, or microbiological property or characteristic that should be within an appropriate limit, range, or distribution to ensure the desired product quality.' Typical mAb CQAs: purity/aggregation, potency, glycosylation (Fc CQA), charge variants, identity, particulates, endotoxin.",
        why:"CQA identification is the cornerstone of QbD — all method development, process characterization, and specification-setting flow from it. Wrong CQA determination means either over-testing unimportant attributes or missing critical safety/efficacy determinants.",
        how:"Read ICH Q8(R2) and A-Mab Case Study Section 3. Build your own CQA risk assessment table for a hypothetical mAb using the FMEA format.",
        ref:"ICH Q8(R2) | ICH Q9 | ICH Q6B | A-Mab Case Study (CASSS 2009)" },
      { id:"t07b", title:"Identity Testing — Peptide Mapping and Primary Sequence Confirmation",
        body:"Peptide mapping by LC-MS/MS is the gold standard for confirming the primary amino acid sequence of a biologic drug substance. The protein is digested with trypsin (or LysC + trypsin) and the resulting peptides separated by RPLC and detected by high-resolution MS (Orbitrap, QTOF). Sequence coverage should be >95%. Beyond identity, peptide mapping detects: deamidation (Asn→Asp), oxidation (Met, Trp), N-terminal pyroglutamate, C-terminal lysine clipping, and disulfide bond assignment.",
        why:"Peptide mapping is a BLA-required identity test. It is also the primary analytical tool for characterizing chemical modifications that may become CQAs. ICH Q6B explicitly requires primary sequence determination for therapeutic proteins.",
        how:"Review your program's peptide map report. Check sequence coverage achieved. Ask your mentor: which modified peptides are monitored as CQAs vs. characterized only?",
        ref:"ICH Q6B §3.2.S.3 | ICH Q2(R2) | FDA Guidance on Analytical Procedures and Methods Validation" },
      { id:"t07c", title:"Purity Testing — SEC-HPLC and CE-SDS as Orthogonal Methods",
        body:"Size-exclusion HPLC (SEC-HPLC) quantifies high-molecular-weight species (HMWS, dimers, oligomers) and low-molecular-weight species (LMWS, fragments) as % of main peak area. Capillary electrophoresis with SDS (CE-SDS), in both reducing (r-CE-SDS) and non-reducing (nr-CE-SDS) conditions, provides size-based purity by electrophoretic mobility. These orthogonal methods detect different aggregate/fragment populations and are both required in BLA release specifications.",
        why:"SEC-HPLC and CE-SDS are complementary — SEC detects non-covalent aggregates in native conditions, while CE-SDS under reducing conditions reveals covalent chain cleavages. Using both prevents missing impurity populations detectable by only one method.",
        how:"Read USP <1058> on analytical instrument qualification for HPLC. Review your SEC-HPLC method validation report — verify system suitability, linearity, and precision data are complete.",
        ref:"ICH Q6B | ICH Q2(R2) | USP <1058> | FDA Guidance on Analytical Methods" },
      { id:"t07d", title:"Potency Assay Design — MOA-Linked Requirements",
        body:"FDA's 2008 Potency Guidance requires potency assays that reflect the mechanism of action (MOA). For anti-cancer mAbs with ADCC mechanism: NK cell-based cytotoxicity assay or Jurkat ADCC reporter assay. For receptor-blocking mAbs: receptor binding inhibition assay. For enzyme inhibitors: enzyme activity assay. Relative potency (% RA vs reference standard) is the industry format, with acceptance criteria typically 70–130% RA or 80–125% RA. Cell-based assays have higher variability (15–25% CV) vs. binding assays (<10% CV).",
        why:"FDA increasingly challenges potency assays that only measure binding without reflecting MOA. A binding ELISA reported as the potency assay will receive regulatory questions. The 2008 guidance makes MOA linkage a firm expectation.",
        how:"Read FDA 2008 Potency Guidance (14 pages) in full. For your program's molecule, identify the MOA and confirm the potency assay reflects it. Ask your mentor: was our potency assay accepted without question by FDA?",
        ref:"FDA Potency Guidance (2008) | ICH Q6B | 21 CFR 610.10 | USP <1032>" },
      { id:"t07e", title:"Glycan CQA Characterization — N-Glycan Profiling",
        body:"N-glycan characterization uses: (1) Released glycan analysis by 2-AB or RapiFluor-MS HILIC labeling + fluorescence/MS detection for glycan species quantification (G0F, G1F, G2F, Man5, afucosylated); (2) Monosaccharide composition analysis; (3) Site-specific glycosylation by LC-MS peptide mapping; (4) Sialic acid quantitation (important for complement activation and clearance). For Fc CQA mAbs, galactosylation (G1F+G2F %) affects complement activation; fucosylation affects ADCC; high mannose affects clearance rate.",
        why:"Glycosylation is simultaneously a CQA (effector function, PK) and a CPV monitoring attribute. Glycan shifts during manufacturing are one of the first indicators of process changes or deviations. ICH Q6B requires glycan characterization for all glycosylated biologics.",
        how:"Review your program's glycan characterization data. Identify which glycan species are release CQAs vs. characterization-only. Ask your mentor: which glycan species has the tightest specification and why?",
        ref:"ICH Q6B | FDA Guidance on Analytical Characterization | USP <1085> on Glycan Analysis" },
      { id:"t07f", title:"Charge Variant Analysis — CEX and icIEF",
        body:"Charge variants arise from: deamidation (creates acidic variants), methionine oxidation (creates acidic variants), C-terminal lysine (creates basic variants), N-terminal pyroglutamate (neutral), succinimide formation (creates basic), and glycation. Cation exchange HPLC (CEX) separates variants by surface charge at low pH. Imaged capillary isoelectric focusing (icIEF) provides pI-based separation and quantification as % acidic/main/basic. Both methods are BLA release tests with linked specifications.",
        why:"Charge variant shifts in stability studies are frequently the first indication of formulation instability, with deamidation rates predictable from Asn-X dipeptide context. Uncontrolled charge variant profiles are a common inspection finding.",
        how:"Review your icIEF and CEX method validation reports. Ask your mentor: which charge variants are controlled by specifications vs. reported only? Are any charge variants linked to potency?",
        ref:"ICH Q6B | ICH Q2(R2) | USP <1053> on Capillary Electrophoresis" },
      { id:"t07g", title:"Reference Standard Establishment and Bridging Studies",
        body:"A primary reference standard (PRS) is a thoroughly characterized, highly purified lot of drug substance used to calibrate all quantitative assays. USP <1033> provides a framework for biologic reference standard establishment. The PRS must be characterized by all CQA methods (potency, purity, glycan, charge variants, peptide map). When the PRS supply approaches depletion, a bridging study demonstrates comparability of the new PRS to the old — every result for the product's remaining commercial life is anchored to the bridge study.",
        why:"Reference standard bridges are among the most consequential analytical CMC decisions. A failed or improperly executed bridge study creates uncertainty in all prior and future lot-release data. FDA expects documented reference standard management procedures.",
        how:"Read USP <1033>. Ask your mentor: how many vials of current PRS remain — when must the next bridge study be initiated? Review the most recent PRS characterization report.",
        ref:"USP <1033> | FDA Reference Standard Guidance (2018) | ICH Q6B" },
      { id:"t07h", title:"Multi-Attribute Monitoring (MAM) by LC-MS",
        body:"Multi-attribute monitoring uses high-resolution LC-MS/MS (peptide map format) to simultaneously quantify multiple product quality attributes in a single analysis: oxidation, deamidation, glycan peptide abundance, N-terminal pyroglutamate, C-terminal lysine, disulfide scrambling, and novel peak detection. MAM can replace multiple individual methods (CEX for deamidation monitoring, SEC for peptide-level fragmentation detection) with a single more informative assay. FDA and EMA are receptive to MAM as a release or stability-monitoring tool.",
        why:"MAM is a paradigm shift in analytical control strategy — one LC-MS method simultaneously monitors dozens of PTMs, reducing testing burden, improving sensitivity, and enabling lot-to-lot CQA trending at unprecedented granularity.",
        how:"Read Rogers et al. MAbs 2015;7:881. Read FDA MAM Workshop (2018) proceedings. Ask your mentor: are we implementing MAM for release testing or stability monitoring?",
        ref:"FDA MAM Workshop (2018) | Rogers RS et al. MAbs 2015;7:881-90 | EMA Reflection Paper on MAM" },
    ],
    questions:[
      { id:"q07a", level:"Foundational", q:"What is a CQA and how is a risk-based CQA identification process conducted for a standard mAb?", why:"CQA identification is the cornerstone of QbD — all method development and spec setting flows from it.", how:"Read ICH Q8(R2) and A-Mab Case Study. Build a CQA risk assessment table.", ref:"ICH Q8 | ICH Q9 | ICH Q6B | A-Mab Case Study" },
      { id:"q07b", level:"Foundational", q:"What is a potency assay and what does 'MOA relevance' mean in FDA's potency testing expectations?", why:"FDA's 2008 guidance requires assays reflecting biological activity attributable to the MOA.", how:"Read FDA 2008 Potency Guidance. Ask: how was our potency assay designed?", ref:"FDA Potency Guidance (2008) | ICH Q6B | 21 CFR 610.10" },
      { id:"q07c", level:"Intermediate", q:"What are the ICH Q2(R2) validation parameters for a quantitative HPLC release method?", why:"Method validation is a legal requirement. ICH Q2(R2) was updated in 2023.", how:"Read ICH Q2(R2) (2023). Create a validation plan template for SEC-HPLC.", ref:"ICH Q2(R2) | USP <1225>" },
      { id:"q07d", level:"Advanced", q:"How do you establish a primary reference standard and conduct a bridging study when the primary supply is exhausted?", why:"Reference standard bridges anchor all lot-release decisions for the remaining product lifecycle.", how:"Read USP <1033>. Ask your mentor: when must the next reference standard bridge be initiated?", ref:"USP <1033> | FDA Reference Standard Guidance (2018) | ICH Q6B" },
      { id:"q07e", level:"Expert", q:"What is multi-attribute monitoring (MAM) and how does implementing it as a release test change the analytical control strategy and regulatory filing?", why:"MAM replaces multiple individual methods with one LC-MS method monitoring dozens of PTMs simultaneously.", how:"Read Rogers et al. 2015 and FDA 2018 MAM workshop proceedings.", ref:"FDA MAM Workshop (2018) | EMA Reflection Paper on MAM | Rogers et al. 2015" },
    ]
  },
  { id:"s08", stage:"08", label:"Formulation Development", sub:"Drug Product", icon:"💊", accent:"#FB923C",
    topics:[
      { id:"t08a", title:"Excipient Selection and Forced Degradation Studies",
        body:"Standard biologic formulation platform: buffer (histidine pH 5.5–6.0 or citrate pH 6.0–6.5 for stability), tonicity agent (sucrose 5–10% or mannitol 5%), surfactant (PS20 0.01–0.05% or PS80 0.02–0.1%), and for lyophilized products a lyoprotectant (sucrose or trehalose as bulking/stabilizing agent). Forced degradation studies expose the formulation to: heat (40°C, 25°C), light (ICH Q1B), freeze-thaw cycles, agitation (rocker), and low/high pH to identify the primary degradation pathways and select conditions that best suppress them.",
        why:"Every excipient is BLA-registered — changing one post-approval requires a PAS. Forced degradation reveals formulation weak points before committing to ICH stability studies. An excipient changed without a stability study creates regulatory exposure.",
        how:"Read Daugherty & Mrsny Drug Discov Today 2006;11:258. Write a one-sentence scientific justification for each excipient in a hypothetical histidine-sucrose-PS80 mAb formulation.",
        ref:"ICH Q8 | ICH Q6B | ICH Q3E | ICH Q1A(R2)" },
      { id:"t08b", title:"Buffer System and pH Optimization",
        body:"Buffer system selection balances: protein stability at chosen pH (determined by charge, conformation), buffering capacity (pKa range — histidine pKa 6.0 is ideal for SC mAb products), injection tolerability (phosphate buffers poorly tolerated subcutaneously, histidine well-tolerated), and freeze/thaw behavior (phosphate buffer crystallizes during freezing, causing pH excursions). pH is the most critical formulation parameter for chemical stability — typically 1–2 pH unit difference dramatically affects deamidation and hydrolysis rates.",
        why:"Buffer choice is irreversible post-BLA registration. Phosphate buffer crystallization during DS frozen storage causes pH excursions that increase aggregation — a common root cause of DS stability failures not discovered until late development.",
        how:"For your program's buffer system, verify: pKa at 5°C (pH changes with temperature), freeze-thaw pH shift tested, and subcutaneous tolerability for SC products. Read Ohtake et al. J Pharm Sci 2011 on buffer selection.",
        ref:"ICH Q8 | ICH Q1A(R2) | USP <1> pH measurement" },
      { id:"t08c", title:"Surfactant Selection — PS20 vs PS80 and Degradation Risk",
        body:"Polysorbate 20 (PS20) and PS80 prevent interfacial denaturation/aggregation during manufacturing stresses (filling, shipping, freeze-thaw). PS80 (oleate-rich) is more susceptible to enzymatic hydrolysis by HCP lipases (PLBL2) than PS20 (laurate-rich). PS20 is increasingly preferred in new formulations for its superior chemical stability. PS degradation generates free fatty acids that form sub-visible particles — a documented recall cause. Polysorbate quality is specified by ester content, fatty acid profile, and absence of peroxides.",
        why:"Polysorbate degradation in commercial products has caused visible and sub-visible particle formation leading to FDA recalls and regulatory action. The choice of PS20 vs PS80 and the polysorbate quality specification are critical formulation decisions.",
        how:"Read Doshi et al. J Pharm Sci 2015. Ask your formulation team: why was PS20 vs PS80 chosen? Is polysorbate purity (ester content, fatty acid profile) in the excipient specification?",
        ref:"ICH Q6B | ICH Q3E | Doshi et al. J Pharm Sci 2015;104:1099-115" },
      { id:"t08d", title:"Container Closure System — Vials, PFS, and Auto-Injectors",
        body:"Container closure systems (CCS) for biologics include: glass vials (type I borosilicate, USP <660>), pre-filled syringes (PFS) with plunger stoppers, and auto-injector devices for self-administration. Each system has specific extractables/leachables profiles, container-closure integrity test (CCIT) requirements, and compatibility studies. Glass delamination (tungsten residues from PFS syringe barrels), silicone oil (from syringe lubrication — causes protein aggregation), and rubber stopper leachables are critical concerns.",
        why:"Container closure system is a BLA-registered component. Silicone oil from PFS has been directly linked to protein aggregation and immunogenicity. Tungsten residues from syringe barrel forming cause protein aggregation. These failure modes must be characterized pre-BLA.",
        how:"Read USP <660> on containers for injections. Ask your packaging team: what extractables/leachables studies were conducted for our CCS? Was tungsten characterized for PFS formats?",
        ref:"ICH Q3E | USP <660> | USP <1> | FDA Guidance on Container-Closure Systems (1999)" },
      { id:"t08e", title:"Lyophilization Cycle Development and Scale-Up",
        body:"Lyophilization (freeze-drying) removes water through sublimation under vacuum. Primary drying removes frozen water; secondary drying removes bound water to target residual moisture (typically <1% for proteins). Shelf temperature during primary drying must remain below the product collapse temperature (Tc) or glass transition temperature (Tg') of the maximally freeze-concentrated solution. Tc characterization by freeze-dry microscopy (FDM) or differential scanning calorimetry (mDSC) is required. Scale-up from lab to manufacturing lyophilizer requires heat transfer coefficient matching.",
        why:"Collapse during primary drying causes cosmetically unacceptable product, reduced reconstitution time, and potentially compromised stability. Residual moisture exceeding specification drives protein degradation. Lyophilization cycle development is among the most technically complex formulation activities.",
        how:"Read Nail & Akers J Pharm Sci 2003 on lyophilization principles. Ask your formulation team: what is Tc for our product and how was it measured? What is the residual moisture specification and its scientific justification?",
        ref:"FDA Lyophilization Guidance | ICH Q8 | USP <1> | USP <731> Loss on Drying" },
      { id:"t08f", title:"High-Concentration mAb — Viscosity and Self-Association",
        body:"High-concentration mAb formulations (>100 mg/mL for subcutaneous delivery) often exhibit solution viscosity >10 cP, challenging subcutaneous auto-injector dosing and fill-finish operations. Viscosity arises from mAb self-association driven by hydrophobic and electrostatic interactions at high concentration. Viscosity reduction strategies: arginine addition, histidine acetate buffers, reduced pH, addition of NaCl or NaSCN (but may affect stability). Viscosity is measured by cone-and-plate rheometry or falling ball viscometer.",
        why:"Viscosity >10 cP in a PFS formulation exceeds most auto-injector injection force limits. This discovery late in development can require complete formulation reformulation. High-concentration mAb formulation viscosity must be measured during feasibility, not post-BLA.",
        how:"For high-concentration programs, measure viscosity at 2°C, 25°C, and 40°C. Ask your formulation team: what was the maximum concentration achieved and the corresponding viscosity? Was arginine evaluated for viscosity reduction?",
        ref:"ICH Q8 | USP <912> Viscosity | FDA Guidance on Drug Products for SC Injection" },
      { id:"t08g", title:"Extractables and Leachables Assessment per ICH Q3E",
        body:"ICH Q3E (2024) provides guidance on extractables/leachables (E&L) for parenterals. Extractables: compounds extracted from contact materials under exaggerated conditions (reflux, elevated temperature). Leachables: compounds that migrate into the drug product under normal use conditions. Threshold for Analytical Evaluation (TAE): 1.5 µg/day threshold for genotoxic compounds per ICH M7; non-volatile leachables: ≥0.05 µg/day SCT. All leachables identified above reporting threshold require safety assessment.",
        why:"Silicone oil from syringe barrels, DEHP from tubing, Irganox from single-use bags, and rubber stopper degradants have all caused protein aggregation or safety concerns in commercial biologics. ICH Q3E (2024) significantly updated requirements vs. previous practices.",
        how:"Read ICH Q3E (2024) in full — focus on Tables 1-3 for extractables protocols and thresholds. Ask your packaging team: when was the E&L study conducted and has ICH Q3E been applied retroactively?",
        ref:"ICH Q3E (2024) | ICH M7(R1) | BPOG Extractables Guidance | USP <661>" },
      { id:"t08h", title:"In-Use and In-Process Hold Studies",
        body:"In-use stability studies simulate conditions of clinical use after opening/dilution: IV bag compatibility (concentration range, diluent compatibility — NS, D5W), in-use hold time at room temperature, and light exposure. In-process hold studies validate storage of DS, DP intermediates, and formulated bulk between manufacturing steps. Hold conditions (temperature, maximum time, mixing strategy) are validated and filed as manufacturing controls. Excursion above hold time limits triggers a deviation.",
        why:"In-use stability governs pharmacy practice and clinical labeling. Inadequate in-use data forces conservative labeling (short hold times) that increases pharmacy workload and waste. Missing in-process hold data is an inspection finding — any step without validated hold conditions is uncontrolled.",
        how:"Review your program's in-use stability and in-process hold study reports. Confirm: IV dilution compatibility across claimed concentration range, and maximum hold times at each DS/DP processing step.",
        ref:"ICH Q1A(R2) | ICH Q8 | FDA Guidance on In-Use Stability Testing (2004)" },
    ],
    questions:[
      { id:"q08a", level:"Foundational", q:"What are the standard excipients in a biologic drug product and what is the scientific rationale for each?", why:"Every excipient is BLA-registered — cannot be changed post-approval without a PAS.", how:"Read Daugherty & Mrsny 2006. Justify each excipient in one sentence.", ref:"ICH Q8 | ICH Q6B | ICH Q3E" },
      { id:"q08b", level:"Intermediate", q:"What are extractables and leachables and how are they assessed per ICH Q3E (2024)?", why:"Leachables (silicone oil, tungsten, stopper degradants) have caused protein aggregation and recalls.", how:"Read ICH Q3E (2024). Ask your mentor: what E&L findings occurred for our CCS?", ref:"ICH Q3E | USP <661> | BPOG E&L Guidance" },
      { id:"q08c", level:"Intermediate", q:"What are the primary and secondary drying phases of lyophilization and why is knowledge of Tc critical?", why:"Primary drying shelf temperature must stay below Tc to prevent product collapse.", how:"Read Nail & Akers on lyophilization. Ask: how was Tc characterized?", ref:"FDA Lyophilization Guidance | ICH Q8 | USP <1>" },
      { id:"q08d", level:"Advanced", q:"How do you set and justify drug product release specifications under ICH Q6B?", why:"Spec setting requires clinical justification plus manufacturing capability. Regulators challenge specs without scientific basis.", how:"Read ICH Q6B and FDA 2014 specifications Q&A.", ref:"ICH Q6B | FDA Specifications Q&A (2014) | ICH Q1E" },
    ]
  },
  { id:"s09", stage:"09", label:"Technology Transfer", sub:"Site Transfers", icon:"🔄", accent:"#F59E0B",
    topics:[
      { id:"t09a", title:"Transfer Package & Site Comparability",
        body:"The technology transfer package is a formal dossier compiled by the sending site covering all unit operations: Master Batch Records (MBRs), SOPs, raw material specifications, equipment qualification requirements, Process Description Document (PDD), analytical method procedures, process flow diagrams, in-process control ranges, and a Transfer Plan with pre-defined acceptance criteria. The receiving site cannot manufacture GMP batches without a complete transfer package. Gaps in documentation — 'tribal knowledge' residing only in people's heads — are the primary cause of transfer failures.",
        why:"Tech transfer failures cost millions in delayed product launches and failed GMP batches. Regulatory agencies inspect transfer documentation — an incomplete transfer package is a Form 483 observation.",
        how:"Read ISPE Technology Transfer Guide and PDA TR65. Ask your mentor: what documents comprised our last DS tech transfer package, and were any knowledge gaps discovered during the transfer?",
        ref:"ICH Q10 | ISPE Technology Transfer Guide | PDA TR65 | ICH Q5E" },
      { id:"t09b", title:"Risk-Based Transfer Planning and Critical Parameter Identification",
        body:"Effective tech transfer begins with a risk assessment (FMEA) identifying which process parameters, raw materials, and equipment types carry the highest transfer risk — those that are most scale-dependent, vendor-specific, or difficult to reproduce. Risk ranking drives the depth of the transfer plan: high-risk steps require additional engineering runs, on-site expert support, and enhanced comparability testing. Transfer risk registers are living documents updated through execution.",
        why:"Addressing risk up front prevents expensive surprises during GMP run execution. A poorly planned transfer that fails at the GMP run stage can delay BLA filing by 12+ months.",
        how:"Read ISPE Technology Transfer Guide Chapter 3 on risk assessment. For one unit operation in your process, list the top 5 transfer risks and how each would be mitigated.",
        ref:"ICH Q9 | ISPE Technology Transfer Guide | PDA TR65" },
      { id:"t09c", title:"Scale-Dependent Process Parameters — Bioreactor and Purification Scale-Up",
        body:"Bioreactor scale-up requires matching key scale-dependent parameters: volumetric oxygen mass transfer coefficient (kLa), specific power input (P/V), CO2 removal, heat transfer, mixing time (θ), and tip speed. Chromatography column scale-up requires maintaining linear velocity, bed height, and residence time while changing column diameter. Membrane filtration scale-up uses area-proportional scaling. Each scale-dependent parameter must be characterized and documented in the transfer package.",
        why:"A bioreactor scaled purely by volume without matching kLa or CO2 stripping has resulted in commercial-scale culture collapses. Chromatography transfer failures from mismatched residence times have produced OOS product quality results.",
        how:"For your bioreactor process, calculate P/V and kLa at lab scale and manufacturing scale. Ask your process development team: which parameters were most challenging to match during our last scale-up?",
        ref:"ICH Q11 | Junker 2004 (scale-up criteria) | ISPE Technology Transfer Guide" },
      { id:"t09d", title:"Analytical Method Transfer — Protocol Design and Statistical Acceptance Criteria",
        body:"Analytical method transfer ensures that a method performs equivalently at the receiving laboratory. Transfer approaches per USP <1224>: complete transfer (comparison study), partial transfer (method verification only), or co-validation. A transfer protocol must pre-define acceptance criteria — typically equivalence intervals around means, %RSD targets, system suitability parameters — and specify the experimental design (analysts, days, instruments, lots). Results are evaluated statistically before GMP release methods are activated at the receiving lab.",
        why:"Analytical method failures post-transfer are a common source of OOS investigations. Pre-defined acceptance criteria are mandatory — evaluating results against post-hoc criteria is specification shopping.",
        how:"Read USP <1224> and the EMA 2014 Bioanalytical Method Validation Guideline. Draft a transfer protocol for a HPLC purity method including a sample size calculation.",
        ref:"USP <1224> | ICH Q2(R1) | EMA Analytical Method Transfer Guideline | ICH Q5E" },
      { id:"t09e", title:"CMO/CDMO Selection, Due Diligence, and Quality Agreement",
        body:"Contract Manufacturing Organization (CMO) selection requires technical due diligence (site audits, process capability, equipment fit), regulatory due diligence (inspection history, Form 483s, Warning Letters), and quality system evaluation. Quality Technical Agreements (QTAs) per ICH Q10 Annex 1 define responsibilities for batch record review, release testing, deviations, CAPA, stability, and regulatory filings. The QTA must be executed before GMP manufacturing begins.",
        why:"FDA holds both the originator and the CMO responsible for cGMP. A CMO Warning Letter can shut down your supply chain. Inadequate quality agreements create ambiguity in deviation management.",
        how:"Read ICH Q10 Annex 1 on Quality Agreements. Ask your quality team: what are the top 5 provisions in our CMO QTA and how are they monitored?",
        ref:"ICH Q10 Annex 1 | 21 CFR 211 | EU GMP Chapter 7 | PDA TR81" },
      { id:"t09f", title:"Process Description Document (PDD) and Knowledge Capture",
        body:"The Process Description Document is the master narrative document that translates the commercial manufacturing process from development knowledge into a format usable by a GMP manufacturing site. It describes each unit operation mechanistically — not just 'what' but 'why' — capturing the relationship between parameters and product quality. The PDD is the primary vehicle for preventing knowledge loss during scientist attrition and is the foundation of the BLA Module 3.2.S.2.2 manufacturing description.",
        why:"Undocumented process understanding is lost when key scientists leave. Companies that lack comprehensive PDDs struggle during regulatory inspections and comparability studies post-transfer.",
        how:"Ask your process development team to walk you through the PDD for one DS unit operation. Note any gaps between what is documented and what the scientists know.",
        ref:"ICH Q10 | ICH Q11 | ICH M4Q (Module 3.2.S.2.2) | ISPE Technology Transfer Guide" },
      { id:"t09g", title:"Engineering Runs, PPQ Readiness, and Regulatory Filing of Transfer",
        body:"Engineering (non-GMP) runs at the receiving site verify equipment performance, staff training, and process behavior before GMP manufacturing. The number of engineering runs required depends on process complexity and transfer risk. Following successful engineering runs, PPQ batches are manufactured under full GMP conditions per the pre-approved PPQ protocol. Transfer outcomes — comparability, analytical equivalence — are documented in a transfer report filed as part of the supplemental BLA or CMC data package.",
        why:"Skipping engineering runs and proceeding directly to GMP batches increases the risk of costly GMP failures. Regulatory filings for site additions require demonstration of comparability, not just batch release.",
        how:"Review the transfer report from a recent CMO transfer. Identify which comparability attributes were selected and how acceptance criteria were set.",
        ref:"ICH Q5E | FDA Post-Approval Changes Guidance | PDA TR65 | ICH Q11" },
    ],
    questions:[
      { id:"q09a", level:"Foundational", q:"What key documents form the foundation of a biologic technology transfer package and what is the critical difference between a transfer plan and a batch record?", why:"'Tribal knowledge' staying in people's heads causes transfer failures. Inadequate documentation is a primary cause of CMO manufacturing failures.", how:"Read ISPE Technology Transfer Guide. Ask your mentor: were there knowledge gaps in our last transfer?", ref:"ICH Q10 | ISPE Technology Transfer Guide | PDA TR65" },
      { id:"q09b", level:"Advanced", q:"How do you design a site comparability study per ICH Q5E for first GMP batches at a new site, including analytical panel selection and statistical acceptance criteria?", why:"Site comparability is a regulatory requirement. Pre-defined criteria are essential — setting them after seeing data is specification shopping, a regulatory integrity violation.", how:"Read ICH Q5E. Draft a comparability acceptance criteria table.", ref:"ICH Q5E | FDA Comparability Guidance (2003) | ICH Q2(R2)" },
    ]
  },
  { id:"s10", stage:"10", label:"Clinical Manufacturing", sub:"Phase 1→3", icon:"🏭", accent:"#2DD4BF",
    topics:[
      { id:"t10a", title:"cGMP, Data Integrity & IND Evolution",
        body:"cGMP for biologics is governed by 21 CFR 210/211 and 600/610 (US) and EU GMP Part I plus Annex 2 (biologics) in Europe. FDA's 2018 data integrity guidance mandates ALCOA+ principles: data must be Attributable, Legible, Contemporaneous, Original, Accurate, and additionally Complete, Consistent, Enduring, and Available. CMC IND content escalates from Phase 1 (limited analytical characterization, proposed specifications) through Phase 3 (commercial-scale process, validated methods, qualified reference standards).",
        why:"Data integrity failures — including backdating records, not recording errors, and copying data — are the most serious GMP violation and can result in import alerts and consent decrees affecting the entire product portfolio.",
        how:"Read 21 CFR 210/211 and FDA 2018 data integrity guidance. Create a side-by-side comparison of US vs EU data integrity requirements.",
        ref:"21 CFR 210/211 | 21 CFR 600/610 | EU GMP Annex 2 | FDA Data Integrity Guidance (2018)" },
      { id:"t10b", title:"Phase 1 CMC Requirements — IND Module 3 Content",
        body:"Phase 1 IND requires: drug substance description and manufacturing summary (3.2.S), drug product description and manufacturing summary (3.2.P), proposed release specifications with acceptance criteria rationale, reference standard characterization, CCS description, and safety-relevant impurities data (residual solvents, heavy metals, microbial limits). Release specifications at Phase 1 are intentionally broad — they will be refined with clinical and analytical data through Phase 2/3. Phase 1 manufacturing can occur at a development-scale GMP facility.",
        why:"FDA can place an IND on clinical hold if CMC data is insufficient for Phase 1 safety. CMC deficiencies at IND are most efficiently resolved before first-in-human (FIH) manufacturing.",
        how:"Read FDA's Phase 1 CMC Guidance (2008). Create a checklist of Phase 1 IND CMC requirements for a mAb program.",
        ref:"FDA Phase 1 CMC Guidance (2008) | 21 CFR 312.23 | ICH M4Q | ICH Q6B" },
      { id:"t10c", title:"Phase 2 CMC Bridging — Comparability Across Process Changes",
        body:"Phase 2 is the period of highest CMC process change frequency: process improvements (titer, yield), scale-up from Phase 1 to Phase 3 scale, analytical method improvements, and formulation optimization. Each change requires a comparability assessment per ICH Q5E — analytical comparability demonstrating equivalent CQA profiles. Changes that cannot demonstrate analytical comparability require clinical bridging (PK/PD studies or additional Phase 1 trials). The CMC comparability strategy must be proactively designed — not reactive.",
        why:"Inadequate comparability documentation for Phase 2 process changes is one of the most common CMC deficiencies in BLAs. FDA may require additional clinical studies if comparability is not adequately demonstrated.",
        how:"Read ICH Q5E. For one process change in your program, design a comparability analytical panel: which CQAs, which methods, which acceptance criteria?",
        ref:"ICH Q5E | FDA Comparability Guidance (2003) | ICH Q6B | ICH Q2(R1)" },
      { id:"t10d", title:"Phase 3 CMC Package — Commercial Process Lock and Validation Readiness",
        body:"Phase 3 CMC represents the lock of the commercial process — the drug substance and drug product must be manufactured by the same process, at the same scale, and at the same site as proposed for commercial approval. Phase 3 CMC milestones: commercial site qualification, Phase 3 analytical methods validated per ICH Q2, reference standard qualification, process characterization studies complete (to support design space), and PPQ protocol drafted. The commercial process must be used for Phase 3 clinical batches.",
        why:"Phase 3 batches manufactured by a process that changes before BLA create a comparability burden. Comparability failures discovered at Phase 3 can require additional clinical studies — the highest-cost and longest-delay CMC problem.",
        how:"Create a Phase 3 CMC readiness checklist for a mAb program, mapping each CMC milestone to its target completion quarter relative to Phase 3 initiation.",
        ref:"FDA Phase 2/3 CMC Guidance | ICH Q11 | ICH Q5E | ICH M4Q" },
      { id:"t10e", title:"IND on Clinical Hold — CMC Causes and Prevention",
        body:"FDA can place an IND on clinical hold under 21 CFR 312.42 for CMC deficiencies that present unreasonable risk to subjects: inadequate drug substance characterization, sterility testing failures, insufficient viral safety data, or missing toxicology batch information. FDA must respond within 30 days of an IND submission. A complete response to a clinical hold requires resolving all deficiencies; FDA has 30 days to evaluate the response. Most CMC holds are avoidable with thorough IND preparation and pre-IND meetings.",
        why:"An IND clinical hold can delay program timelines by 3-12 months. Most CMC holds result from insufficient characterization data or inadequate specifications that FDA deems insufficient for patient safety assessment.",
        how:"Review FDA's list of reasons for clinical hold under 21 CFR 312.42. Ask your regulatory team: have we ever received an IND clinical hold and what caused it?",
        ref:"21 CFR 312.42 | FDA Phase 1 CMC Guidance | ICH Q6B | PDA TR54" },
      { id:"t10f", title:"Clinical Supply Chain Management and Comparator Drug Procurement",
        body:"Clinical supply chain management includes: labeling (blinding/unblinding strategy), cold chain management (temperature monitors, qualified shipper validation), import/export permits, batch traceability through IRT/IVRS systems, expiry management and resupply planning. Comparator drug procurement for active-controlled trials must document authenticity, supply chain integrity, and label compliance per EU Clinical Trials Regulation 536/2014 and FDA requirements.",
        why:"Clinical supply chain failures — mislabeled or expired drug product reaching patients, broken cold chain — are patient safety events and regulatory violations. Inadequate supply planning creates study delays.",
        how:"Ask your clinical supply team: how are temperature excursions during clinical shipments handled? What happens if a site receives a compromised shipment?",
        ref:"21 CFR 312 | EU Clinical Trials Regulation 536/2014 | ICH E6(R3) | ISPE CSMS Guide" },
      { id:"t10g", title:"Reference Standard Qualification — Primary, Secondary, and Working Standards",
        body:"Reference standards are the measurement anchor for potency, identity, and purity assays. Primary reference standard (PRS): extensively characterized (structure, activity, purity, homogeneity), used to calibrate secondary standards. Secondary/working reference standards: qualified relative to PRS, used for routine lot testing. Qualification requires: full analytical panel, potency assignment relative to WHO/NIBSC international standard where applicable, and formal qualification report per ICH Q6B.",
        why:"Reference standard degradation without detection causes lot-to-lot potency drift that is undetectable without a stable, well-characterized standard. An unqualified reference standard used for release testing is a cGMP violation.",
        how:"Read ICH Q6B Section on reference standards. Ask your analytical team: when was our primary reference standard last requalified and what triggered the requalification?",
        ref:"ICH Q6B | USP <1033> | WHO International Standards | PDA TR56" },
    ],
    questions:[
      { id:"q10a", level:"Foundational", q:"What is cGMP and which US and EU regulations govern biological drug substance and drug product manufacturing? What are the main differences between US and EU requirements?", why:"cGMP is the minimum quality standard required by law. FDA can place an IND on clinical hold for cGMP deficiencies.", how:"Read 21 CFR 210/211, 600/610. Read EU GMP Part I and Annex 2. Create a comparison table.", ref:"21 CFR Parts 210/211 | 21 CFR 600/610 | EU GMP Annex 2" },
      { id:"q10b", level:"Intermediate", q:"How does the CMC section of an IND evolve from Phase 1 through Phase 3, and which CMC activities most commonly become critical-path risks to BLA filing if not initiated early enough?", why:"Many programs fail at BLA because CMC wasn't upgraded adequately between Phase 2 and 3.", how:"Draw a CMC lifecycle Gantt from Phase 1 IND to BLA. Ask your mentor: what CMC activity most threatened our last BLA timeline?", ref:"FDA Phase 1 CMC Guidance | FDA Phase 2/3 CMC Guidance | ICH M4Q" },
    ]
  },
  { id:"s11", stage:"11", label:"Process Characterization", sub:"CPP / Design Space", icon:"🎯", accent:"#F472B6",
    topics:[
      { id:"t11a", title:"FMEA, Risk Assessment, and Parameter Classification",
        body:"Process characterization begins with a risk assessment — typically Failure Mode and Effects Analysis (FMEA) — classifying each process parameter as: potential Critical Process Parameter (pCPP, requires characterization studies to determine impact on CQAs), Key Process Parameter (KPP, affects yield/efficiency not CQAs), or Non-Key Parameter (demonstrated no effect within ranges studied). Risk ranking is based on severity of potential CQA impact × probability of occurrence × detectability. The FMEA output directly drives the experimental design for characterization studies.",
        why:"An underpowered risk assessment that misclassifies pCPPs as non-key results in inadequate BLA data and potential regulatory deficiencies. ICH Q9 requires risk management to be systematic and documented.",
        how:"Read ICH Q9 and the A-Mab Case Study (CASSS 2009). Run a mock FMEA for 5 bioreactor parameters, scoring each on severity, occurrence, and detectability.",
        ref:"ICH Q9 | A-Mab Case Study | ICH Q11 | ICH Q8(R2)" },
      { id:"t11b", title:"Small-Scale Model Qualification — Scale-Down Model Development",
        body:"Characterization studies are performed at laboratory scale using qualified scale-down models (SDMs) that mimic commercial-scale behavior. SDM qualification demonstrates that the lab-scale model is representative: product quality attributes (CQAs) and process performance (yields, in-process results) match at commercial scale across a range of parameter settings. Acceptable qualification requires statistical equivalence — typically within ±15% for continuous attributes. An unqualified SDM cannot support CPP classification in a BLA.",
        why:"A scale-down model that does not accurately predict commercial-scale behavior generates misleading characterization data. FDA can reject CPP classifications based on unqualified SDMs.",
        how:"Read PDA TR60 on scale-down model qualification. For one unit operation, describe the experimental design for qualifying a 3L bioreactor as a scale-down model for a 2000L commercial bioreactor.",
        ref:"ICH Q11 | PDA TR60 | A-Mab Case Study | FDA Process Validation Guidance (2011)" },
      { id:"t11c", title:"Design of Experiments — Screening and Response Surface Methodologies",
        body:"Statistical Design of Experiments (DoE) systematically evaluates process parameter effects while minimizing experimental runs. Screening DoEs (Resolution IV fractional factorials, Plackett-Burman) identify main effects with potential confounding — used for initial pCPP identification. Response surface methodologies (Central Composite Design, Box-Behnken) characterize curvature and interactions for confirmed CPPs. DoE analysis uses ANOVA, regression modeling, and residual analysis. The design space emerges from the response surface model with defined confidence intervals.",
        why:"One-factor-at-a-time (OFAT) studies miss interaction effects — two parameters that individually appear non-critical may have a critical joint effect that OFAT never discovers. DoE is required for ICH Q8 design space establishment.",
        how:"Read ICH Q8 Annex on design space. Learn JMP or Minitab design and analysis tools. Run a simple 2^3 full factorial DoE in JMP/Excel to understand main effects and interactions.",
        ref:"ICH Q8(R2) | ICH Q11 | JMP Statistical Software | Box, Hunter & Hunter (Statistics for Experimenters)" },
      { id:"t11d", title:"CPP Classification — Statistical vs. Practical Significance",
        body:"A parameter with a statistically significant effect on a CQA (p < 0.05) is not automatically a CPP. ICH Q8 requires judgment about practical significance — whether the magnitude of the effect across the studied range has clinical relevance. If a parameter's effect on a CQA is statistically significant but the CQA remains well within specification across the full parameter range (including edge of failure), a non-CPP classification may be scientifically defensible with appropriate documentation. The distinction determines NOR vs. PAR vs. design space designation.",
        why:"Over-classifying parameters as CPPs increases regulatory filing burden for every future change. Under-classifying genuine CPPs creates uncontrolled process risk. This classification decision has long-term commercial consequences.",
        how:"Read ICH Q8(R2) Section 2.5 on CPP classification. For your program, identify one parameter that was borderline — how was the classification decision documented and justified?",
        ref:"ICH Q8(R2) | ICH Q9 | A-Mab Case Study (Section 5)" },
      { id:"t11e", title:"Normal Operating Range (NOR), Proven Acceptable Range (PAR), and Design Space",
        body:"NOR (Normal Operating Range): the target range within which the process is routinely operated — filed in batch records. PAR (Proven Acceptable Range): the wider range demonstrated acceptable by characterization studies — a parameter excursion into the PAR but outside NOR triggers a deviation but not necessarily batch rejection. Design space: the multidimensional combination of input variables demonstrated to provide assurance of quality — movement within design space is not a regulatory filing requirement (ICH Q8). Each concept represents a different level of operational flexibility.",
        why:"Confusing NOR, PAR, and design space leads to either unnecessarily tight operational constraints (if NOR is filed as PAR) or inadequate controls (if PAR boundaries are not supported by characterization data).",
        how:"Read ICH Q8(R2) definition section. For one CPP from your program, draw a diagram showing the NOR, PAR, and edge-of-failure zones.",
        ref:"ICH Q8(R2) | ICH Q11 | FDA Process Validation Guidance (2011)" },
      { id:"t11f", title:"CQA Linkage — Connecting Process Parameters to Patient Safety",
        body:"The characterization program must explicitly link CPPs to CQAs and CQAs to clinical relevance. This linkage — parameter → CQA → clinical/safety outcome — is the foundation of the QbD regulatory story in BLA Module 3. For biologics, the linkage is often: bioreactor pH → glycosylation pattern (CQA) → Fc effector function / immunogenicity risk (clinical). Mechanistic models (where available) can quantitatively predict CQA outcomes from process parameter variations, providing additional regulatory confidence.",
        why:"FDA reviewers assess whether CPP classifications are scientifically grounded in patient impact. A characterization program that identifies CPPs without demonstrating clinical relevance of the affected CQAs is incomplete.",
        how:"For your top CPP-CQA pair, write a 3-sentence mechanistic explanation linking the parameter to the CQA to the patient outcome.",
        ref:"ICH Q8(R2) | ICH Q6B | ICH Q11 | A-Mab Case Study" },
      { id:"t11g", title:"Edge-of-Failure Studies and Multivariate Process Controls",
        body:"Edge-of-failure (EOF) studies deliberately push parameters to extremes beyond the PAR to understand failure modes and margin to failure. EOF data supports the NOR/PAR rationale — demonstrating that the margin from operational range to failure is adequate. Multivariate process controls integrate multiple CQA-relevant parameters into a combined control strategy: if pCPPs interact, a multivariate acceptable region (not single-parameter PAR) must be defined and controlled. Modern PAT tools (spectroscopy, soft sensors) can monitor multiple parameters simultaneously for real-time multivariate control.",
        why:"Regulators increasingly expect characterization programs to define failure modes, not just characterize within acceptable ranges. Understanding failure modes enables better risk management and deviation investigation.",
        how:"Ask your process development team: what failure modes were identified for our top CPP and at what parameter level does failure occur?",
        ref:"ICH Q8(R2) | ICH Q9 | ICH PAT Guidance (2004) | FDA Process Validation Guidance (2011)" },
    ],
    questions:[
      { id:"q11a", level:"Foundational", q:"What is the difference between a CPP, KPP, and non-key parameter? Give concrete examples for a bioreactor step and explain the regulatory implications of each classification.", why:"Parameter classification is a regulatory commitment. CPPs have direct CQA impact — changing them requires a regulatory filing.", how:"Read ICH Q8 definitions. Classify pH, DO, feed volume, and agitation for your bioreactor.", ref:"ICH Q8 | ICH Q9 | ICH Q11" },
      { id:"q11b", level:"Intermediate", q:"How do you set the NOR and PAR for a CPP and what manufacturing flexibility does the design space concept provide compared to operating strictly within the NOR?", why:"Design space gives manufacturers ability to adjust within a pre-approved range without a regulatory filing.", how:"Read ICH Q8 Annex on design space. Ask your mentor: for one of our CPPs, what is the NOR vs PAR boundary?", ref:"ICH Q8(R2) | FDA Process Validation Guidance" },
      { id:"q11c", level:"Advanced", q:"Your DoE shows load challenge has a statistically significant effect on HCP clearance (20 vs 18 ng/mg) — both well within specification. Should it be classified as a CPP? Defend your scientific and regulatory reasoning.", why:"Statistical significance does not equal practical significance. ICH Q8 allows scientific judgment — if the effect is within spec and lacks clinical relevance, a non-CPP classification may be defensible.", how:"Read ICH Q8 on statistical vs. practical significance. Discuss with your mentor: what documentation would support a non-CPP classification?", ref:"ICH Q8(R2) | ICH Q9" },
    ]
  },
  { id:"s12", stage:"12", label:"Process Validation", sub:"PPQ & Lifecycle", icon:"✅", accent:"#38BDF8",
    topics:[
      { id:"t12a", title:"FDA 2011 Three-Stage Validation Lifecycle",
        body:"FDA's 2011 Process Validation Guidance replaced the outdated '3 successful GMP batches = validated' paradigm with a science and risk-based lifecycle approach. Stage 1 (Process Design): all development, characterization, and scale-up activities. Stage 2 (Process Performance Qualification — PPQ): commercial-scale confirmation with pre-defined acceptance criteria in a PPQ protocol that must be approved before the first PPQ batch. Stage 3 (Continued Process Verification — CPV): ongoing statistical monitoring of the commercial process using control charts and capability indices to detect drift before specification failures.",
        why:"Stage 3 is perpetual — validation is never complete. Companies that treat validation as a one-time event miss process drift signals and face unexpected batch failures.",
        how:"Read FDA's 2011 Process Validation Guidance (24 pages) in full. Create a table mapping each Stage 1, 2, and 3 deliverable to a specific program milestone.",
        ref:"FDA Process Validation Guidance (2011) | ICH Q10 | ICH Q11" },
      { id:"t12b", title:"PPQ Protocol Design — Pre-Defined Acceptance Criteria",
        body:"The PPQ protocol is a formal GMP document that defines, before manufacturing begins: the number of PPQ batches (typically 3 for a new process), the specific CQA and process performance tests to be evaluated, the acceptance criteria for each test (typically ≥ individual lot release specifications), and the statistical approach. The protocol must be approved by QA, Manufacturing, Regulatory, and Process Development before the first PPQ batch. Post-hoc modification of acceptance criteria after seeing data constitutes 'specification shopping' — a data integrity violation.",
        why:"FDA inspectors request PPQ protocols. Acceptance criteria documented after data collection are an inspection observation. Three PPQ batches is a minimum — additional batches may be required for high-risk processes.",
        how:"Draft a PPQ protocol outline for a Protein A capture step: what parameters would you measure, what acceptance criteria would you set, and how would you handle a marginal result?",
        ref:"FDA Process Validation Guidance (2011) | 21 CFR 211 | ICH Q8 | ICH Q10" },
      { id:"t12c", title:"Continued Process Verification (CPV) — Statistical Process Control",
        body:"Stage 3 CPV uses statistical process control (SPC) charts — Individuals/Moving Range (I-MR), X-bar R, Exponentially Weighted Moving Average (EWMA) — to monitor key process indicators and CQAs over commercial batches. Process capability indices: Cp (potential, based on specification width vs. process variation) and Cpk (actual, adjusted for centering). Cpk ≥ 1.33 is the typical minimum target for critical attributes (4-sigma process margin). Annual CPV reports summarize process state of control and identify improvement opportunities.",
        why:"CPV detects process drift months before batch failures occur. Companies without formal Stage 3 programs face surprise OOS results and reactive recall investigations. FDA inspectors request CPV data.",
        how:"Read ASTM E2587 on control charts for pharmaceutical manufacturing. For one release attribute, draw an I-MR chart using the last 15 batch results and calculate Cpk.",
        ref:"FDA Process Validation Guidance (2011) | ASTM E2587 | ICH Q10 | Juran Quality Handbook" },
      { id:"t12d", title:"Aseptic Process Simulation (Media Fill) — Sterility Assurance",
        body:"Aseptic Process Simulation (APS, or media fill) validates the sterility assurance of aseptic fill-finish operations by replacing drug product with sterile microbiological growth medium (tryptic soy broth), filling units under GMP conditions, and incubating for 14 days. Acceptance criterion: zero contaminated units for < 5,000 units filled; one contamination in 5,000–10,000 is investigation-triggering; > 1 contamination invalidates the media fill. APS must simulate worst-case conditions: longest allowed interventions, maximum operating time, minimum staff. EU GMP Annex 1 (2022 revision) extensively updated APS requirements.",
        why:"Sterility failures in commercial biologics can result in patient deaths. A failed media fill can suspend fill-finish operations for months while root cause is investigated. EU GMP Annex 1 (2022) is significantly more demanding than the 2008 version.",
        how:"Read EU GMP Annex 1 (2022) Section on APS. Create a checklist of worst-case conditions that must be simulated in a media fill for a mAb vial filling operation.",
        ref:"EU GMP Annex 1 (2022) | FDA Sterile Drug Products Guidance (2004) | PDA TR22" },
      { id:"t12e", title:"Cleaning Validation for Multi-Product Biological Manufacturing",
        body:"Cleaning validation demonstrates that cleaning procedures reduce product residues, cleaning agent residues, bioburden, and endotoxin to levels that do not compromise the next product (or environment). Acceptance limits are set using toxicological data: for potent biologics, Maximum Allowable Carryover (MACO) is calculated from the No Observable Effect Level (NOEL) or Acceptable Daily Exposure (ADE) × safety factor. Worst-case matrix: product most difficult to clean (hardest to remove, lowest ADE), equipment with most complex geometry, shortest cleaning cycle. Analytical methods for residue detection must be sensitive to at least 10% of the limit.",
        why:"Multi-product manufacturing facilities without validated cleaning risk cross-contamination — a patient safety issue and a regulatory violation. FDA has issued Warning Letters for inadequate cleaning validation using insufficient analytical detection limits.",
        how:"Read FDA's 2017 Process Validation Guidance update on cleaning validation. Calculate the MACO for a mAb with a therapeutic dose of 2 mg/kg in a 1000L bioreactor.",
        ref:"FDA Guide to Inspections: Cleaning Validation (1993) | EMA Guideline on Cleaning Validation | PDA TR29 | ICH Q3C" },
      { id:"t12f", title:"Computer System Validation (CSV) and 21 CFR Part 11 Compliance",
        body:"Computer System Validation (CSV) per GAMP 5 (Good Automated Manufacturing Practice) validates that computerized systems used in GMP manufacturing (MES, LIMS, BMS, SCADA, DCS) are fit for intended use and meet data integrity requirements. GAMP 5 risk-based approach classifies software by category: Category 4 (configurable, e.g., LIMS) and Category 5 (custom, requires highest validation effort). 21 CFR Part 11 (US) and EU GMP Annex 11 (EU) govern electronic records and signatures — requiring audit trails, user access controls, and data backup/disaster recovery.",
        why:"Computerized system deficiencies (insufficient audit trails, shared logins, lack of change control) are a top FDA inspection observation category. A LIMS audit trail gap can call into question the integrity of thousands of GMP records.",
        how:"Read GAMP 5 and 21 CFR Part 11. For one GMP system in your facility (LIMS, MES, or DCS), identify the CSV validation category and list the required validation deliverables.",
        ref:"GAMP 5 (ISPE) | 21 CFR Part 11 | EU GMP Annex 11 | FDA 2003 Part 11 Guidance" },
      { id:"t12g", title:"PPQ Failure Investigation and Remediation",
        body:"A PPQ acceptance criteria failure requires immediate deviation opening, Phase 1 laboratory investigation (sample and data integrity confirmation), Phase 2A expanded investigation (manufacturing process review), and Phase 2B root cause investigation — identical in structure to a commercial OOS investigation. Batch disposition requires QA determination. PPQ program failure (multiple failures, no identifiable root cause) may require re-initiation of Stage 1 process development activities. FDA must be notified if PPQ failure affects approved CMC data (supplemental BLA).",
        why:"A PPQ failure at the third batch is a high-stakes event — a CMC leadership judgment call with BLA timeline implications. The investigation must be completed before proceeding to the next PPQ batch.",
        how:"Build a PPQ failure decision tree: deviation → root cause type (assignable vs. not) → disposition options → regulatory notification assessment.",
        ref:"FDA Process Validation Guidance (2011) | FDA OOS Guidance (2006) | 21 CFR 211.192" },
    ],
    questions:[
      { id:"q12a", level:"Foundational", q:"What are the three stages of FDA's 2011 process validation lifecycle, what is the key deliverable of each, and why is Stage 3 described as 'perpetual'?", why:"FDA's 2011 guidance replaced the 3-batch paradigm. Stage 3 is perpetual because commercial process monitoring never ends.", how:"Read FDA's 2011 PV Guidance in full. Create a one-page summary table.", ref:"FDA Process Validation Guidance (2011) | ICH Q10 | ICH Q11" },
      { id:"q12b", level:"Intermediate", q:"What elements must a PPQ protocol contain and why must it be approved before the first PPQ batch is manufactured?", why:"Pre-defined acceptance criteria are essential — setting them after seeing data is 'specification shopping,' a regulatory integrity violation.", how:"Draft a PPQ protocol outline for a bioreactor step. Ask your mentor: who reviews and approves our PPQ protocol?", ref:"FDA Process Validation Guidance (2011) | 21 CFR 211 | ICH Q8" },
      { id:"q12c", level:"Advanced", q:"What is Stage 3 Continued Process Verification (CPV) and what statistical tools detect process drift before batches fail specification?", why:"Companies neglecting CPV risk process drift going undetected until batch failure. FDA inspectors request CPV data.", how:"Read FDA 2011 PV Guidance Stage 3. Learn Shewhart control charts and Cpk/Ppk interpretation.", ref:"FDA Process Validation Guidance (2011) | ASTM E2587 | ICH Q10" },
      { id:"q12d", level:"Expert", q:"During execution of your final PPQ batch, a critical IPC result falls outside the pre-defined acceptance criterion. What are your immediate steps, investigation approach, and batch disposition decision framework?", why:"A PPQ failure at the last batch is high-stakes — a CMC leadership judgment call with BLA timeline implications.", how:"Build a flowchart: deviation → Phase I → Phase II → assignable cause assessment → disposition.", ref:"FDA PV Guidance (2011) | FDA OOS Guidance (2006) | 21 CFR 211.192" },
    ]
  },
  { id:"s13", stage:"13", label:"Commercial Manufacturing", sub:"GMP Operations", icon:"🏭", accent:"#22D3EE",
    topics:[
      { id:"t13a", title:"Annual Product Quality Review (APQR) and Change Control",
        body:"APQR (US: Product Quality Review per 21 CFR 211.180(e); EU: Annual Product Review per EU GMP Chapter 1; ICH Q10) is a systematic annual review compiling all quality data for each product: batch release results, OOS/OOT occurrences, deviations and CAPAs, change controls implemented, stability data, CPV statistical outputs, complaint trends, and regulatory commitments. The APQR must identify any trends, confirm process control, evaluate change effectiveness, and recommend improvements. Post-approval changes are classified: Annual Report (AR), CBE-0 (Comparability Protocol), CBE-30, or Prior Approval Supplement (PAS) per 21 CFR 601.12.",
        why:"FDA inspectors specifically request APQRs. An APQR that fails to identify a concerning stability or process trend is a Form 483 observation — demonstrating that the quality system failed to detect a known risk.",
        how:"Read 21 CFR 211.180(e), EU GMP Chapter 1, and ICH Q10. Ask your quality team: what was the most significant finding from last year's APQR and what action was taken?",
        ref:"21 CFR 211.180(e) | EU GMP Chapter 1 | ICH Q10 | FDA Post-Approval Changes Guidance" },
      { id:"t13b", title:"Batch Release — QP Decision, Certificate of Analysis, and Disposition",
        body:"Commercial batch release requires: review of completed batch record (MBR/electronic), review of all in-process and release test results vs. specifications, deviation and exception review, environmental monitoring data review, and QA disposition (release or rejection). In the EU, a Qualified Person (QP) is legally responsible for each released batch (EU GMP Part I Chapter 2). FDA requires an authorized quality unit. The Certificate of Analysis (CoA) — the formal release document — must match the specification filed in the BLA/NDA and be archived for the product lifetime.",
        why:"Releasing a non-conforming batch is a serious GMP violation. The QP can face personal liability for regulatory violations in the EU. CoA errors (wrong specifications, missing tests) are a common inspection observation.",
        how:"Review a commercial CoA for a biologic product. Identify each specification and cross-reference it to the filed BLA specification. Confirm all required tests are present.",
        ref:"EU GMP Part I Chapter 2 | 21 CFR 211 | ICH Q6B | 21 CFR 601.12" },
      { id:"t13c", title:"Manufacturing Deviations, CAPA, and Batch Disposition",
        body:"A deviation is any unplanned departure from an approved GMP procedure, specification, or environmental limit. Deviations are categorized by risk: Critical (potential patient safety impact — immediate QA escalation), Major (potential product quality impact — full investigation required), and Minor (no product quality impact, no investigation required). Root cause investigation follows the Phase 1/2A/2B framework (per FDA OOS Guidance for product impact). CAPA (Corrective and Preventive Action) addresses root cause and prevents recurrence. Batch disposition decisions — release, reprocess, rework, or reject — require QA and often regulatory input for critical deviations.",
        why:"A deviation closed with 'cause unknown' is an unresolved quality risk. Repeat deviations with ineffective CAPAs are a pattern FDA inspectors specifically review.",
        how:"Review the last 5 deviations in your manufacturing area. For each: Was the root cause truly identified? Was the CAPA specific and measurable? Was effectiveness verified?",
        ref:"21 CFR 211.192 | FDA OOS Guidance (2006) | ICH Q10 | EU GMP Chapter 9" },
      { id:"t13d", title:"Environmental Monitoring and Contamination Control Strategy (CCS)",
        body:"EU GMP Annex 1 (2022) requires a formal Contamination Control Strategy (CCS) — a holistic facility-wide program addressing personnel hygiene and behavior, cleanroom design, HVAC, gowning, disinfection and sterilization, environmental monitoring (EM), and process design. EM programs monitor: viable airborne (active air sampling by RCS/Anderson impactor), viable surface (contact plates, swabs), non-viable airborne particulate (continuous particle counters), and personnel (finger dabs, surface contact). Action and alert limits per ISO 14644 and Annex 1 Grade definitions (A/B/C/D). Excursions trigger immediate investigation and disposition review.",
        why:"Environmental monitoring excursions that are inadequately investigated — especially repeat isolates of the same organism — indicate a systemic contamination control failure and are cited during FDA and EMA inspections.",
        how:"Read EU GMP Annex 1 (2022) Section 9 on EM. Create a CCS summary for a mAb fill-finish facility: list the key elements and how each is controlled.",
        ref:"EU GMP Annex 1 (2022) | ISO 14644 | USP <1116> | FDA Sterile Drug Products Guidance (2004)" },
      { id:"t13e", title:"Supply Chain Resilience and Raw Material Risk Management",
        body:"Supply chain risk management for commercial biologics includes: single-source raw material risk assessment, supplier qualification and incoming material testing strategy, safety stock determination, approved alternate supplier qualification, and supply continuity planning. Single-source bioreactor media components, specific membrane grades, and glass vials are common supply chain vulnerabilities. Raw material quality impacts — changes in vendor manufacturing process for cell culture media components have affected bioreactor performance and product glycosylation without the manufacturer's disclosure.",
        why:"Raw material supply disruptions have caused drug shortages for critical biologics. An undisclosed raw material change by a supplier caused a protein aggregation OOS event at one commercial manufacturer — a risk only mitigated by proactive change notification agreements.",
        how:"For your commercial product, identify the top 3 single-source raw materials. For each, document: supplier backup plan, incoming testing scope, and requalification trigger criteria.",
        ref:"ICH Q11 | ICH Q10 | USP <1079.1> | FDA Supply Chain Security Guidance" },
      { id:"t13f", title:"Field Alert Reports and Recall Management",
        body:"Field Alert Reports (FARs) per 21 CFR 600.14 must be filed within 3 business days of becoming aware of: distributed product failing specifications, bacterial contamination of any lot, product mix-up, defective packaging/labeling, or distributed product that is stable but fails to meet specifications. Recall management follows FDA's recall classification (Class I: reasonable probability of serious adverse health consequence; Class II: temporary adverse health consequences; Class III: unlikely to cause adverse health consequences) with mandatory recall strategy and health hazard assessment. Mock recalls and recall readiness assessments are GMP requirements.",
        why:"The failure to file a required FAR — discovered by FDA through a field complaint or inspection — results in a Warning Letter and enforcement action. Mock recall exercises reveal logistical gaps that only emerge during actual recall execution.",
        how:"Read 21 CFR 600.14 on FARs. Review your company's recall SOP. Ask: when was our last mock recall conducted and what gaps did it identify?",
        ref:"21 CFR 600.14 | 21 CFR Part 7 | FDA Recall Guidance | ICH Q10" },
      { id:"t13g", title:"FDA GMP Inspection Readiness — Data Room and CMC Documentation",
        body:"FDA PAI (Pre-Approval Inspection) and GMP surveillance inspections assess: batch record completeness and data integrity, OOS investigation quality, deviation and CAPA effectiveness, change control documentation, environmental monitoring trends, calibration and qualification records, and training records. The CMC data room — a compilation of process characterization, validation, and stability data organized by manufacturing step — is best practice for pre-inspection preparation. FDA inspectors use the BPDR (Biological Product Deviation Report) system for biologics. Inspection readiness programs include mock inspections, executive briefing documents, and SME (Subject Matter Expert) preparation.",
        why:"Inadequate inspection preparation — inspectors discovering data integrity issues, unresolved deviations, or inconsistencies between records and BLA data — can result in Warning Letters and import alerts that halt commercial supply.",
        how:"Read FDA's Guide to Inspections of Pharmaceutical Quality Control Laboratories (1993) and EMA GMP inspection findings reports. Ask your quality team: when was our last mock inspection and what observations did it generate?",
        ref:"FDA PAI Guidance | 21 CFR Part 600 | ICH Q10 | PDA TR41" },
    ],
    questions:[
      { id:"q13a", level:"Foundational", q:"What is an APQR and what information must it compile? What regulatory deficiency arises from an APQR that fails to identify a concerning manufacturing trend?", why:"FDA inspectors request APQRs. A poor APQR missing concerning trends is an inspection finding.", how:"Read 21 CFR 211.180(e) and EU GMP Chapter 1. Ask your mentor: what was the key APQR finding last year?", ref:"21 CFR 211.180(e) | EU GMP Chapter 1 | ICH Q10" },
      { id:"q13b", level:"Intermediate", q:"How do you classify a post-approval manufacturing change under FDA's biologics reporting framework (PAS/CBE-30/CBE-0/Annual Report)?", why:"Incorrect classification is a regulatory violation — filing a PAS change as an Annual Report can result in a Warning Letter.", how:"Read FDA 2004 post-approval guidance. Build a change categorization decision tree.", ref:"FDA Post-Approval Changes Guidance (2004) | ICH Q12 | 21 CFR 601.12" },
      { id:"q13c", level:"Expert", q:"A field complaint reports visible particulates in your commercial drug product. Walk through your immediate regulatory reporting obligations, investigation steps, and supply continuity considerations.", why:"Product quality complaints leading to recalls are the highest-consequence commercial CMC events. Field Alert Reports must be filed within 3 business days.", how:"Read 21 CFR 600.14 on Field Alert Reports. Read FDA recall guidance.", ref:"21 CFR 600.14 | FDA Recall Guidance | ICH Q10" },
    ]
  },
  { id:"s14", stage:"14", label:"Stability & Shelf Life", sub:"ICH Q5C", icon:"📅", accent:"#4ADE80",
    topics:[
      { id:"t14a", title:"ICH Q5C Biologic Stability Program Design",
        body:"ICH Q5C (biologic stability) requires: long-term real-time conditions (2–8°C for refrigerated products, -20°C for frozen), accelerated conditions (25°C/60%RH), and stress studies. Time points: 0, 3, 6, 9, 12, 18, 24 months, then annually. Critical difference from small molecules (ICH Q1A): accelerated stability data for biologics CANNOT generally be used for shelf-life extrapolation or prediction — real-time data under actual storage conditions is required. Analytical panel for biologics must include stability-indicating methods for potency, aggregation, fragmentation, glycosylation, and oxidation.",
        why:"Biologic stability cannot use accelerated data for extrapolation — this is a regulatory requirement unique to biologics. Missing time points create permanent data gaps that regulators will cite in the BLA review.",
        how:"Read ICH Q5C and Q1A(R2) side by side. Build a full stability protocol matrix for a liquid mAb at 2–8°C: conditions, time points, and analytical panel.",
        ref:"ICH Q5C | ICH Q1A(R2) | ICH Q1E | ICH Q6B" },
      { id:"t14b", title:"Forced Degradation Studies — Stress Protocol per ICH Q1B",
        body:"Forced degradation (stress testing) characterizes degradation pathways and identifies stability-indicating methods. Stress conditions: thermal (40°C, 60°C for short periods), hydrolysis (acid 0.01–0.1N HCl, base 0.01–0.1N NaOH), oxidative (hydrogen peroxide 0.003–0.3% H2O2), photolytic (ICH Q1B: 1.2 million lux hours visible, 200 W·h/m² UV), and mechanical (freeze-thaw, agitation). Degradation products identified by mass spectrometry and chromatographic methods. Forced degradation typically induces 10–30% degradation to identify products — not representative of storage conditions but essential for method validation (specificity).",
        why:"A stability-indicating method that cannot distinguish intact drug from degraded product will pass degraded lots. Forced degradation is mandatory for method validation specificity demonstration per ICH Q2(R1).",
        how:"Read ICH Q1B photostability guidance. Design a forced degradation protocol for a mAb: which conditions, concentrations, time points, and analytical methods?",
        ref:"ICH Q1B | ICH Q2(R1) | ICH Q5C | USP <1085>" },
      { id:"t14c", title:"Freeze-Thaw and Mechanical Stress Studies for Biologics",
        body:"Biologics, particularly monoclonal antibodies, are vulnerable to freeze-thaw stress (ice crystal formation, cryo-concentration of excipients, pH shifts) and mechanical stress (shaking, shipping vibration, fill-finish pump shear). Freeze-thaw studies evaluate: number of cycles, container size, thaw rate, and mixing after thaw. Acceptance criteria: aggregation, potency, and subvisible particle counts. Shipping simulation studies (ASTM D4169, ISTA standards) validate packaging integrity and product stability under worst-case distribution conditions. Freeze-thaw and shipping validation are required before commercial distribution.",
        why:"A mAb that aggregates during freeze-thaw of the DS bulk or during shipping to the clinical site is an invisible patient safety risk — subclinical aggregation can cause immunogenic reactions.",
        how:"Ask your analytical and formulation teams: what freeze-thaw studies were conducted and what was the worst CQA response observed? Was shipping simulation conducted at commercial scale?",
        ref:"ICH Q5C | ICH Q1A(R2) | ASTM D4169 | ISTA 2A/2B Protocols" },
      { id:"t14d", title:"Statistical Methods for Shelf-Life Estimation (ICH Q1E)",
        body:"ICH Q1E provides statistical methods for shelf-life estimation from real-time stability data. For small molecules (and some biologics where applicable): linear regression of degradation data with 95% confidence interval intersection with specification limit determines shelf life. For biologics: extrapolation to only 1.5× the observed data range is permitted (conservative vs. small molecules). Statistical approaches: pool batches if slopes and intercepts are not statistically different (F-test, α=0.25); if different, use worst-case batch. Minimum 3 batches per stability program. For frozen biologics, T90 is the standard shelf-life descriptor.",
        why:"Incorrect shelf-life calculation — either too conservative (short shelf life, commercial impact) or too liberal (shelf-life extension beyond supported data) — has regulatory consequences. ICH Q1E statistical methods are required for BLA shelf-life justification.",
        how:"Read ICH Q1E in full. Download the FDA Stability Module for JMP or R. Run a regression analysis on a 24-month stability dataset to calculate shelf life with 95% CI.",
        ref:"ICH Q1E | ICH Q5C | ICH Q1A(R2) | USP <1195>" },
      { id:"t14e", title:"Photostability Testing per ICH Q1B",
        body:"ICH Q1B requires photostability testing as part of the stress testing program for drug substance and drug product. Option 1: ICH 1 (overall illumination ≥1.2 million lux hours) and ICH 2 (UV energy ≥200 W·h/m²) — typical industry choice. Option 2: confirm photostability by option 1 exposure; if degradation occurs, evaluate as appropriate. Testing applies to bulk DS, DP container closure system, and direct patient presentation (if unpackaged use). Photolabile biologics require amber vials, light-protective packaging, or product label instructions limiting light exposure.",
        why:"Photodegradation discovered after BLA submission requires CCS changes (amber vials, packaging design changes) — these are post-approval changes requiring supplements. Early photostability characterization prevents late-stage package redesign.",
        how:"Ask your analytical team: were photostability studies conducted for DS and DP? Was the packaging confirmed to provide adequate light protection?",
        ref:"ICH Q1B | ICH Q5C | ICH Q2(R1) | USP <1191>" },
      { id:"t14f", title:"Post-Approval Stability Commitments and Shelf-Life Extension",
        body:"Post-approval stability commitments define the ongoing stability program the manufacturer commits to during BLA/NDA review: at minimum one batch per year per strength/container combination put on stability, with annual reporting in the APQR and any OOT/OOS results reported as stability failures. Shelf-life extension after approval requires a stability supplement (typically CBE-30 for extensions supported by BLA commitment data; PAS if significant methodology changes or extension beyond precedent). If stability failure occurs post-approval, FDA must be notified under 21 CFR 314.81.",
        why:"Failing to meet post-approval stability commitments — not placing required batches, missing time points, not reporting failures — is a regulatory violation. Proactive shelf-life extension, using commitment data, is a commercial priority for aging product.",
        how:"Read FDA 2003 Stability Testing Guidance for Human Drugs and Biologics. Ask your stability team: what is the current post-approval commitment for each commercial product?",
        ref:"ICH Q5C | FDA 2003 Stability Guidance | ICH Q1A(R2) | 21 CFR 314.81" },
    ],
    questions:[
      { id:"q14a", level:"Foundational", q:"What ICH guidelines govern stability for biologic drug products and how do they differ from small molecule requirements regarding accelerated condition shelf-life extrapolation?", why:"Unlike small molecules, biologic stability cannot use accelerated data for shelf-life extrapolation — real-time data is required.", how:"Read ICH Q5C and Q1A side by side. Create a comparison table.", ref:"ICH Q5C | ICH Q1A(R2) | ICH Q1E | ICH Q1B" },
      { id:"q14b", level:"Intermediate", q:"How do you design a formal stability protocol for a biologic DS and DP — including storage conditions, time points, and analytical panel selection per ICH Q5C?", why:"Stability studies are irreversible. Missed time points create data gaps regulators cite.", how:"Design a complete stability protocol for a liquid mAb at 5°C.", ref:"ICH Q5C | ICH Q1A(R2) | FDA Stability Guidance" },
      { id:"q14c", level:"Advanced", q:"If a commercial drug product shows an OOT stability result at 24 months but remains within specification, what is the investigation pathway and potential regulatory action?", why:"OOT results require investigation even without a spec failure — the trend may predict a future OOS and may require shelf-life shortening.", how:"Read ICH Q10 on OOT investigations. Build a decision tree.", ref:"ICH Q10 | FDA Stability Guidance | ICH Q5C" },
    ]
  },
  { id:"s15", stage:"15", label:"BLA Filing", sub:"Submissions", icon:"📋", accent:"#F59E0B",
    topics:[
      { id:"t15a", title:"CTD Module 3 Architecture and Quality Overall Summary (QOS)",
        body:"The Common Technical Document (CTD) Module 3 organizes all CMC data: 3.2.S Drug Substance (manufacturer, characterization, manufacture, specifications, reference standards, CCS, stability) and 3.2.P Drug Product (description, manufacture, characterization, specs, reference standards, CCS, stability). The Quality Overall Summary (QOS) precedes Module 3 — the first CMC document a regulatory reviewer reads — and must accurately summarize all Module 3 content in narrative form with integrated justifications. Inconsistencies between the QOS and Module 3 body are a leading cause of deficiency letters.",
        why:"Module 3 is the CMC backbone of every BLA. Regulatory reviewers spend most of their time in 3.2.S and 3.2.P. Gaps, inconsistencies, and missing justifications in these sections are the primary drivers of Complete Response Letters (CRLs).",
        how:"Download ICH M4Q and map every CMC deliverable to a specific CTD section number. Read one BLA Module 3 from FDA's public disclosure database (Drugs@FDA).",
        ref:"ICH M4Q | FDA BLA Guidance | EMA Quality CTD Guidance | ICH Q6B" },
      { id:"t15b", title:"CMC Development History and Comparability Strategy for BLA",
        body:"The BLA 3.2.S.2.6 (Manufacturing Process Development) and 3.2.P.2.1 (DP Development) sections require a complete CMC development history: all process changes from Phase 1 to commercial, analytical bridging/comparability data for each change, and a narrative demonstrating that process understanding evolved through a science-and-risk-based approach. Each process change requires an ICH Q5E comparability assessment with data. The BLA reviewer reconstructs the product's CMC journey — a coherent narrative reduces review time and deficiency risk.",
        why:"Gaps in the CMC development history — undocumented process changes, missing comparability data — create questions about whether clinical material was representative of the commercial product.",
        how:"Create a CMC change history timeline for your program: list each process change, the phase at which it occurred, and the comparability strategy used.",
        ref:"ICH M4Q (3.2.S.2.6) | ICH Q5E | ICH Q11 | FDA Comparability Guidance (2003)" },
      { id:"t15c", title:"Type A and Type B Pre-BLA Meetings — CMC Questions and FDA Commitments",
        body:"Type B meetings (30-day scheduling, 60-90 days from request to meeting) are the most valuable pre-BLA regulatory interactions. A Pre-BLA Type B meeting allows the sponsor to: clarify data package sufficiency, gain FDA alignment on specification strategies, resolve open CMC questions, and obtain written meeting minutes that constitute regulatory commitments. Questions must be specific and data-supported — FDA cannot provide opinions on hypothetical data. Type A meetings (urgent issues, clinical hold resolution) have a 30-day scheduling requirement.",
        why:"Pre-BLA meetings prevent CRLs. FDA commitments in meeting minutes can prevent deficiencies that would otherwise add 6–18 months of delay. Vague questions receive vague answers — the investment in specific questions with supporting data summaries is high-ROI.",
        how:"Read FDA's Formal Meetings Guidance (2009) and PDUFA procedures. Draft 5 specific CMC questions for a hypothetical pre-BLA meeting for a liquid mAb.",
        ref:"FDA Formal Meetings Guidance (2009) | PDUFA Meeting Procedures | ICH M4Q" },
      { id:"t15d", title:"Complete Response Letters (CRL) — CMC Deficiencies and Prevention",
        body:"A Complete Response Letter (CRL) is issued when FDA cannot approve the BLA as submitted — the applicant must address all CRL deficiencies before resubmission. CMC CRL deficiencies include: insufficient analytical method validation, specifications lacking scientific justification, incomplete comparability data for process changes, manufacturing deviations at PAI, missing data for container-closure integrity testing, and inconsistencies within Module 3. CRL resubmission timelines: Class 1 (3-month review for minor deficiencies), Class 2 (6-month review for major deficiencies). Each CRL month represents lost product revenue and delayed patient access.",
        why:"CMC-related CRLs are preventable with thorough pre-BLA gap analysis and regulatory team alignment. A CMC CRL in a competitive indication can result in a competitor reaching the market first.",
        how:"Review publicly available CRL summaries from FDA's database. Identify the 5 most common CMC-related CRL deficiency categories and how each could be prevented.",
        ref:"FDA CRL Guidance | FDA MaPP 6020.3 | ICH M4Q | FDA BLA Review Guidance" },
      { id:"t15e", title:"Biosimilar BLA (351(k)) vs. Reference Product (351(a)) — CMC Differences",
        body:"A biosimilar BLA under 351(k) of the PHS Act requires a comparison to the Reference Listed Drug (RLD) or Reference Product (RP) at every level: structural, functional, animal, and clinical. CMC requirements for 351(k): extensive analytical comparability (fingerprint-like analysis), manufacturing process description, and DP/DS specifications. The '3+3' development paradigm: analytical comparability, PK, and clinical endpoints. The biosimilar developer cannot use the RP's proprietary process data — the process is independently developed to achieve biosimilarity at the quality attribute level. Interchangeability designation requires switching studies.",
        why:"The biosimilar approval pathway (351(k)) has unique CMC requirements that differ fundamentally from the originator 351(a) pathway. CMC scientists transitioning to biosimilar development must understand these differences.",
        how:"Read FDA's Biosimilar Development Guidance (2019). Compare the Module 3 requirements for a 351(a) originator BLA vs. a 351(k) biosimilar BLA for the same mAb product.",
        ref:"PHS Act Section 351(k) | FDA Biosimilar Guidance (2019) | ICH Q5E | FDA Scientific Considerations for Demonstrating Biosimilarity" },
      { id:"t15f", title:"Rolling Review, Accelerated Approval, and Breakthrough Therapy CMC Implications",
        body:"FDA expedited programs have CMC implications: Breakthrough Therapy Designation (BTD) allows intensive FDA guidance, including on CMC strategy, throughout development; Rolling Review allows submission of completed BLA sections before the full BLA is ready; Accelerated Approval (AA) requires post-marketing confirmatory trial data and may require specific CMC commitments. Each expedited pathway has different PDUFA review timelines (6 months for Priority Review vs. 10 months for Standard). CMC teams must plan BLA sections to be ready for rolling review submission schedules.",
        why:"Breakthrough Therapy Designation can accelerate market access by 2+ years relative to standard review — but only if CMC is ready. CMC delays in a BTD program are particularly costly given the patient need driving the designation.",
        how:"Read FDA's Expedited Programs Guidance (2014). For a BTD program, map the CMC readiness milestones against the accelerated clinical development timeline.",
        ref:"FDA Expedited Programs Guidance (2014) | PDUFA Review Timelines | FDA Rolling Review Guidance" },
      { id:"t15g", title:"FDA CMC Review Process — CDER vs. CBER, Reviewer Expectations",
        body:"Biologics regulated by CBER (Center for Biologics Evaluation and Research): vaccines, blood products, tissues, gene therapy. Biologics regulated by CDER (Center for Drug Evaluation and Research): therapeutic proteins, mAbs, peptides (transferred from CBER in 2003). CBER reviewers historically apply more conservative specifications and require more extensive characterization for vaccines. CDER/Office of Pharmaceutical Quality (OPQ) manages CMC review — the PAI team coordinates with field inspectors. FDA's Integrated Quality Assessment (IQA) approach means CMC reviewers expect sponsors to integrate QbD principles and risk-based justifications.",
        why:"Understanding which FDA Center reviews your product — and the expectations of the specific Office — prevents mismatched assumptions about data requirements.",
        how:"Look up which FDA Center and Division reviews your product type. Read the review templates that FDA publishes for CDER BLA CMC reviews.",
        ref:"FDA CBER/CDER Transfer Policy | FDA IQA Guidance | FDA M4Q Guidance | 21 CFR 601" },
    ],
    questions:[
      { id:"q15a", level:"Foundational", q:"What is the CTD Module 3 structure and what information belongs in 3.2.S (Drug Substance) vs. 3.2.P (Drug Product)?", why:"Module 3 is the CMC module of every IND and BLA. Fluency in CTD architecture prevents both gaps and redundancies.", how:"Download ICH M4Q. Map every CMC deliverable to a specific CTD section number.", ref:"ICH M4Q | FDA BLA Guidance | EMA Quality CTD Guidance" },
      { id:"q15b", level:"Intermediate", q:"What CMC topics should be addressed in a Type B pre-BLA meeting and how must questions be formulated to receive maximally useful FDA commitments?", why:"Pre-BLA meetings prevent CRLs. Specific questions with data summaries can get FDA commitments preventing deficiencies worth 6–18 months of delay.", how:"Read FDA 2009 Formal Meetings Guidance. Draft 5 specific CMC questions for a hypothetical pre-BLA meeting.", ref:"FDA Formal Meetings Guidance (2009) | PDUFA Meeting Procedures" },
      { id:"q15c", level:"Advanced", q:"How do ICH Q8, Q9, Q10, Q11, and Q12 form an integrated Quality framework and what is the practical implication of each for a commercial biologic CMC program?", why:"The ICH Quality guidelines are interdependent. Q8 (design/CQA), Q9 (risk), Q10 (quality system), Q11 (DS development), Q12 (lifecycle) define the modern CMC paradigm.", how:"Read each guideline. Create a one-page integration map.", ref:"ICH Q8(R2) | ICH Q9 | ICH Q10 | ICH Q11 | ICH Q12" },
    ]
  },
  { id:"s16", stage:"16", label:"Post-Approval & Lifecycle", sub:"ICH Q12", icon:"♾️", accent:"#C084FC",
    topics:[
      { id:"t16a", title:"ICH Q12 — Established Conditions, PACMPs, and Lifecycle Management",
        body:"ICH Q12 (2020) established a science-and-risk-based framework for post-approval change management. Established Conditions (ECs): the subset of BLA-filed information whose change triggers a regulatory submission — defined by impact on product quality and clinical performance. Post-Approval Change Management Protocols (PACMPs): pre-agreed frameworks for anticipated future changes (e.g., media supplier change, fill site expansion) that, if pre-approved by FDA, reduce filing category from PAS (12+ months) to CBE-30 (30 days) or lower. Product Lifecycle Management (PLCM) documentation captures all ECs and their change management strategy.",
        why:"Early adopters of PACMPs report significant regulatory time savings for lifecycle manufacturing changes. CMC leaders designing BLA submissions today should include PACMPs for anticipated commercial changes to capture future flexibility.",
        how:"Read ICH Q12 and the Implementation Working Group training materials. Identify one anticipated post-approval change for your product and draft a PACMP outline.",
        ref:"ICH Q12 | FDA Draft Guidance on Q12 Implementation | EMA Q12 Q&A | ICH Q8(R2)" },
      { id:"t16b", title:"Post-Approval Manufacturing Site Transfers",
        body:"Adding or replacing a manufacturing site post-approval requires a regulatory filing — typically a Prior Approval Supplement (PAS) for biologics unless a PACMP or other pre-agreed framework applies. Required data: site qualification (equipment, utilities, personnel), process comparability at the new site per ICH Q5E, analytical method transfer results, first commercial batch (or PPQ batch) data, and regulatory alignment on a comparability protocol. FDA may conduct a PAI of the new site before approval of the supplement. Timeline: PAS review 12 months; with PACMP, potentially CBE-30.",
        why:"Site transfers are among the most complex and time-consuming post-approval CMC activities. Poor planning — initiating a transfer without a clear regulatory filing strategy — can result in supply gaps.",
        how:"Develop a site transfer regulatory strategy for adding a second DS manufacturing site: list the required data package, filing category, and timeline assumptions.",
        ref:"ICH Q12 | ICH Q5E | FDA Post-Approval Changes Guidance | 21 CFR 601.12" },
      { id:"t16c", title:"Comparability Post-Approval — Manufacturing Changes and Biosimilar Competition",
        body:"Post-approval manufacturing changes affecting product quality (process changes, equipment upgrades, raw material changes) require comparability assessments per ICH Q5E demonstrating that the change did not adversely impact product quality. The comparability analytical panel for commercial changes is typically broader than development comparability — including all validated release methods plus extended characterization (glycosylation detail, charge variants, aggregation species). Biosimilar competition changes the calculus: post-approval process changes that shift CQA profiles (even within specification) must be considered in the context of biosimilar comparability claims.",
        why:"A post-approval process change that shifts glycosylation within specification may create a regulatory conflict with a biosimilar that demonstrated similarity to the originator's pre-change product.",
        how:"Read ICH Q5E and the FDA 2003 Comparability Guidance. For a planned media component change, design a comparability analytical panel with pre-defined acceptance criteria.",
        ref:"ICH Q5E | ICH Q12 | FDA Comparability Guidance (2003) | FDA Biosimilar Guidance" },
      { id:"t16d", title:"Global Regulatory Filing Strategy — FDA, EMA, PMDA, NMPA",
        body:"Commercial biologics require simultaneous or sequential filings in multiple markets. Key differences: FDA (BLA, 12-month standard / 6-month priority review) vs. EMA (MAA, Centralized Procedure, 210-day review + clock stops) vs. PMDA/Japan (JNDA, often requires Japan-specific clinical data or bridging study) vs. NMPA/China (NDA/BNDA, technical dossier requirements increasingly ICH-aligned post-2019). ICH M4Q is largely harmonized across markets. Key differences: Japan requires Japanese-language summaries, China requires GMP inspection of manufacturing site, EMA requires QP certification. Simultaneous global filings require coordinated submission timelines.",
        why:"Sequential country-by-country filings delay global revenue by 2-5 years. Simultaneous filing requires all regulatory-ready data packages for all markets — any CMC gap delays the slowest market.",
        how:"Research the regulatory approval timeline for one recently approved biologic in the US, EU, Japan, and China. Identify CMC-specific differences in data requirements.",
        ref:"FDA BLA Guidance | EMA MAA Guidelines | PMDA Guidance on Biologics | NMPA Biologic Guidelines | ICH M4Q" },
      { id:"t16e", title:"Drug Shortage Prevention and Supply Continuity Strategies",
        body:"FDA Drug Shortage Staff tracks at-risk products under 21 CFR 314.81(b)(3)(iii) — manufacturers must notify FDA 6 months in advance of discontinuation or market withdrawal. Supply continuity strategies: multiple qualified manufacturing sites (with approved supplements), safety stock maintenance, dual supply chain for critical raw materials, and robust CPV to detect quality issues before they cause supply interruptions. FDA's Drug Shortage Task Force (2018) identified manufacturing quality as the top cause of shortages — GMP failures, facility shutdowns, and OOS results account for 62% of drug shortage causes.",
        why:"Biologics shortages can be life-threatening for critical-care patients. Beyond patient impact, a drug shortage results in FDA scrutiny, mandatory reporting, and potential FDA facility inspection.",
        how:"Read FDA's Drug Shortage Task Force Report (2019). For your commercial product, identify the top 3 supply chain risks and mitigation strategies.",
        ref:"21 CFR 314.81 | FDA Drug Shortage Task Force Report (2019) | FDA Drug Shortage Guidance" },
      { id:"t16f", title:"Second-Generation Formulation and Delivery System Lifecycle Strategy",
        body:"Lifecycle formulation improvements — from IV to subcutaneous (concentration increase, viscosity), from lyophilized to liquid (stability support), from vial to prefilled syringe/autoinjector — represent significant patient convenience and commercial advantages. These changes require BLA supplements with formulation development data, device compatibility studies (extractables/leachables, functionality), human factors engineering studies (HFE/usability), and comparability data. Combination product submissions (drug + device) require CDER/CDRH co-review. Each formulation improvement must be planned 3–5 years before commercial launch.",
        why:"Second-generation delivery systems (subcutaneous autoinjector) extending market exclusivity and improving patient adherence are among the highest-value post-approval CMC investments. Inadequate formulation lead time causes timeline failures.",
        how:"For a mAb currently approved as an IV infusion, outline the CMC development program required to add a subcutaneous autoinjector presentation.",
        ref:"ICH Q12 | FDA Combination Products Guidance | ICH Q3E | HFE/Usability FDA Guidance (2016)" },
      { id:"t16g", title:"Product Discontinuation, CMC Legacy Documentation, and Knowledge Transfer",
        body:"Product discontinuation requires: FDA notification per 21 CFR 314.81 (6-month advance notice), retained batch records and QC data for regulatory access (21 CFR 211.180 — records retained for product lifetime plus 1 year), CMC knowledge transfer to enable potential future restoration of supply, and archiving of all regulatory correspondence. CMC legacy documentation — complete process knowledge, method data, stability archives — is a corporate asset enabling future reformulation, technology transfer to a new partner, or data mining for platform programs. ALCOA+ principles apply to all retained records.",
        why:"Product discontinuation without proper records management can leave companies unable to defend regulatory decisions made years earlier or respond to future FDA inquiries about historic batches.",
        how:"Review your company's records retention policy for discontinued products. Ask your regulatory affairs team: what CMC documentation is retained post-discontinuation and in what format?",
        ref:"21 CFR 211.180 | 21 CFR 314.81 | ICH Q10 | FDA Records Retention Guidance" },
    ],
    questions:[
      { id:"q16a", level:"Foundational", q:"What is the US post-approval change reporting framework for biologics (PAS/CBE-30/CBE-0/AR) and what drives the category determination for a given manufacturing change?", why:"Incorrect classification is a regulatory violation — filing a PAS change as an Annual Report can result in a Warning Letter.", how:"Read FDA 2004 post-approval guidance. Build a change categorization decision tree.", ref:"FDA Post-Approval Changes Guidance (2004) | ICH Q12 | 21 CFR 601.12" },
      { id:"q16b", level:"Intermediate", q:"What are ICH Q12 Established Conditions (ECs) and PACMPs, and how can a PACMP reduce a PAS timeline (12+ months) to CBE-30 (30 days)?", why:"A well-designed PACMP has direct commercial value for manufacturing lifecycle management.", how:"Read ICH Q12 Sections 3 and 4. Draft a one-page PACMP outline for a raw material supplier change.", ref:"ICH Q12 | FDA Draft PACMP Guidance | EMA PACMP Q&A" },
      { id:"q16c", level:"Expert", q:"A competitor launches a biosimilar to your approved mAb. You are planning 3 manufacturing changes over 3 years that may shift CQA profiles. How do you develop a CMC lifecycle strategy balancing manufacturing economics, regulatory complexity, and biosimilar competitive dynamics?", why:"This synthesis question integrates ICH Q12, comparability strategy, regulatory categorization, biosimilar competition, and manufacturing economics — the kind of strategic thinking CMC directors practice daily.", how:"Develop a 3-year CMC lifecycle plan. For each change: filing category, comparability strategy, biosimilar implication, risk mitigation.", ref:"ICH Q12 | ICH Q5E | FDA Post-Approval Guidance | FDA Biosimilar Guidance" },
    ]
  },
];


export const DOMAINS = [
  { id:"dom_up", label:"Upstream Bioprocess", icon:"🔬", accent:"#22D3EE", desc:"Bioreactor operations, cell culture, media, scale-up, PAT, intensification",
    questions:[
      { id:"du01", level:"Foundational", q:"What is the difference between batch, fed-batch, and perfusion bioreactor modes for mAb production? What are the productivity and product quality trade-offs of each?", why:"Bioreactor mode is a fundamental platform decision affecting titer, product quality, facility fit, and COGS over the entire commercial product lifecycle.", how:"Ask your mentor: why did we choose fed-batch — were alternatives evaluated and what were the COGS implications?", ref:"ICH Q11 | FDA Process Development Guidance" },
      { id:"du02", level:"Foundational", q:"What is viable cell density (VCD), viability, and cell-specific productivity (qP), and why are daily measurements essential for interpreting bioreactor performance?", why:"VCD, viability, and qP together define integrated manufacturing performance. A viability drop below 70–80% is an early signal of metabolic stress that can shift CQAs before any specification failure.", how:"Review your site's bioreactor IPC monitoring system.", ref:"ICH Q11 | FDA Process Validation Guidance" },
      { id:"du03", level:"Intermediate", q:"How does pCO2 accumulation in a large-scale bioreactor affect cell metabolism and glycosylation, and what process strategies control pCO2 in 10,000–20,000L bioreactors?", why:"pCO2 accumulation is a major scale-up challenge — it shifts intracellular pH, inhibits growth, and can alter glycosylation.", how:"Read Mostafa & Gu 2003 on pCO2 effects. Ask your mentor: is pCO2 a CPP in our process?", ref:"ICH Q8 | ICH Q11" },
      { id:"du04", level:"Intermediate", q:"What is the role of copper in CHO cell culture media and what effect does copper concentration have on N-glycosylation, specifically core fucosylation and ADCC activity?", why:"Copper depletion reduces core fucosylation — a deliberate lever for increasing ADCC activity, a CQA for Fc-effector function mAbs.", how:"Read Qian et al. on copper depletion and afucosylation.", ref:"ICH Q8 | ICH Q6B" },
      { id:"du05", level:"Advanced", q:"How do you perform a cell culture process scale-up from 2L SDM to 20,000L commercial bioreactor and what engineering parameters must be maintained or adjusted?", why:"Scale-up is a fundamental CMC challenge. kLa, mixing time, pCO2, shear stress, and nutrient gradients all change with scale.", how:"Read Nienow 2006 on scale-up principles. Ask your mentor: what were the top 3 challenges in our commercial scale-up?", ref:"ICH Q11 | FDA Process Validation Guidance" },
      { id:"du06", level:"Advanced", q:"How do you design a risk-based PAT strategy for a commercial mAb bioreactor process, linking inline and at-line measurements to the formal control strategy?", why:"PAT enables real-time monitoring and control, reducing end-product testing burden and enabling real-time release testing.", how:"Read FDA 2004 PAT Guidance.", ref:"FDA PAT Guidance (2004) | ICH Q8(R2) | ICH Q13" },
      { id:"du07", level:"Expert", q:"A commercial bioreactor run shows unexpectedly high ammonia accumulation not observed in the SDM during characterization. How do you investigate and what are the batch disposition and CMC implications?", why:"SDM representativeness failures have real-time batch disposition and long-term CMC program implications.", how:"Develop an investigation plan. Ask your mentor: has our SDM ever failed to predict a commercial-scale finding?", ref:"ICH Q11 | FDA OOS Guidance (2006) | FDA PV Guidance (2011)" },
      { id:"du08", level:"Expert", q:"What is continuous bioreactor manufacturing and how does ICH Q13 address the unique CMC and process validation challenges, including the regulatory definition of 'batch'?", why:"ICH Q13 (2022) provides the first comprehensive guidance on validation, batch definition, and control strategy for continuous upstream.", how:"Read ICH Q13 on continuous manufacturing for biologics.", ref:"ICH Q13 | ICH Q8 | FDA Continuous Manufacturing Guidance" },
    ]
  },
  { id:"dom_ds", label:"Downstream Purification", icon:"⚗️", accent:"#34D399", desc:"Chromatography, viral clearance, filtration, UF/DF, impurity clearance, resin reuse",
    questions:[
      { id:"dd01", level:"Foundational", q:"What are the key impurities that must be cleared during mAb downstream purification, what are the patient risks of each, and what regulatory specification limits apply?", why:"Impurity clearance is the primary function of downstream processing. Understanding which impurities exist, their risks, and spec limits is essential for designing and defending a purification process.", how:"Build an impurity table: impurity | source | patient risk | regulatory limit | detection method.", ref:"ICH Q6B | FDA HCP Guidance | FDA Residual DNA Guidance" },
      { id:"dd02", level:"Foundational", q:"What is the mechanism of Protein A affinity chromatography, what are the main commercial resin options, and what are the key advantages and limitations of each?", why:"Protein A is the workhorse of mAb capture. CMC leaders must understand the chemistry, resin options, and limitations.", how:"Review the Cytiva and Repligen Protein A resin portfolios.", ref:"ICH Q11 | Cytiva MabSelect Technical Guide | ICH Q6B" },
      { id:"dd03", level:"Intermediate", q:"What is the difference between bind-elute and flow-through chromatography modes and when is each preferred in a mAb polishing sequence?", why:"Mode selection directly affects impurity clearance mechanism and process economics.", how:"Build a table: chromatography step | mode | target impurities | key CPPs.", ref:"ICH Q11 | Shukla et al. 2007 | ICH Q6B" },
      { id:"dd04", level:"Intermediate", q:"What is the orthogonal viral clearance strategy required by ICH Q5A and why must a minimum of two independent clearance steps with different mechanisms be demonstrated?", why:"Orthogonal mechanisms provide independent barriers. If one step fails, the second provides backup. This two-step requirement is a patient safety standard that cannot be waived.", how:"Read ICH Q5A(R1) Section 5. Build a table of clearance mechanisms for each purification step.", ref:"ICH Q5A(R1) | PDA TR41 | FDA Points to Consider (1998)" },
      { id:"dd05", level:"Advanced", q:"How do you develop a process characterization package for a chromatography polishing step (e.g., CEX) including DoE design, CPP classification, and NOR/PAR definition?", why:"Chromatography PC studies are the scientific backbone of BLA Module 3.2.S.2.2.", how:"Build a CEX characterization DoE: factors (pH, conductivity, load challenge, flow rate), responses (HCP, aggregates, yield).", ref:"ICH Q8 | ICH Q11 | FDA Process Validation Guidance" },
      { id:"dd06", level:"Advanced", q:"How do you justify Protein A resin reuse in a BLA and what cycle lifetime studies demonstrate consistent HCP clearance and product quality across the claimed reuse cycles?", why:"Protein A costs $5,000–15,000/L. Reuse justification has both major quality and COGS implications.", how:"Review your Protein A resin lifetime validation report.", ref:"ICH Q11 | ICH Q6B | Cytiva MabSelect Platform Guidance" },
      { id:"dd07", level:"Expert", q:"How would you approach developing a downstream purification process for a bispecific antibody that contains a mixture of homo- and heterodimers requiring separation?", why:"Bispecific antibodies require separation of hetero- from homodimers — a challenge not present in conventional mAbs.", how:"Read Liu et al. on bispecific antibody manufacturing challenges.", ref:"ICH Q11 | ICH Q6B | Bispecific Antibody Manufacturing Literature" },
      { id:"dd08", level:"Expert", q:"You are developing the downstream process for a novel modality (ADC or gene therapy vector). What platform knowledge from mAb purification transfers, and what novel regulatory challenges arise?", why:"Platform extension to novel modalities requires identifying transferable vs. modality-specific process knowledge.", how:"Read FDA guidance on ADC CMC and gene therapy manufacturing.", ref:"FDA ADC CMC Guidance | FDA Gene Therapy CMC Guidance | ICH Q11" },
    ]
  },
  { id:"dom_dp", label:"Drug Product & Formulation", icon:"💊", accent:"#FB923C", desc:"Formulation design, excipients, container-closure, stability, lyophilization, E&L",
    questions:[
      { id:"df01", level:"Foundational", q:"What is protein aggregation, what are the physical and chemical mechanisms driving it in biologics, and how is aggregation risk assessed during formulation development?", why:"Aggregation is the most important immunogenicity CQA for biologics.", how:"Read Roberts 2014 on protein aggregation mechanisms.", ref:"ICH Q6B | USP <787> | ICH Q5C" },
      { id:"df02", level:"Foundational", q:"What are polysorbate 20 and polysorbate 80, why are they used, and what is the PLBL2-mediated polysorbate degradation risk and its clinical consequences?", why:"Polysorbates prevent surface aggregation but are susceptible to enzymatic degradation by PLBL2 and other HCPs. Degradation causes particle formation and product recalls.", how:"Read Labrenz 2014 on PLBL2.", ref:"ICH Q8 | ICH Q3E | ICH Q5C | Labrenz 2014" },
      { id:"df03", level:"Intermediate", q:"What is DSF (differential scanning fluorimetry) and how is it used in formulation screening to rank excipient combinations by thermal stability (Tm)?", why:"DSF is a high-throughput formulation screening tool measuring Tm as a proxy for conformational stability.", how:"Read Niesen et al. 2007 on DSF.", ref:"ICH Q8(R2) | ICH Q5C | Niesen et al. 2007" },
      { id:"df04", level:"Intermediate", q:"What are the primary and secondary drying phases of lyophilization, how is product collapse temperature (Tc) characterized, and why is knowledge of Tc critical?", why:"Primary drying shelf temperature must be below Tc to prevent product collapse.", how:"Read Nail & Akers on lyophilization.", ref:"FDA Lyophilization Guidance | ICH Q8" },
      { id:"df05", level:"Advanced", q:"What are extractables and leachables, how is a safety risk assessment conducted per ICH Q3E (2024), and what analytical tools identify and quantify leachable species?", why:"Leachables from containers have caused protein aggregation and patient safety issues.", how:"Read ICH Q3E (2024) and BPOG extractables guidance.", ref:"ICH Q3E | BPOG E&L Guidance | PDA TR66 | USP <661>" },
      { id:"df06", level:"Advanced", q:"What is the subcutaneous (SC) delivery bioavailability challenge for biologics and what formulation strategies improve bioavailability for high-dose mAbs?", why:"SC delivery achieves only 50–85% bioavailability vs IV. High-dose mAbs face viscosity challenges (>25 cP makes injection painful).", how:"Read Richter & Bhatt 2018 on SC bioavailability.", ref:"ICH Q8 | EMA Reflection Paper on SC Administration" },
      { id:"df07", level:"Expert", q:"Your drug product shows increasing sub-visible particle counts at 9-month real-time stability time points. How do you systematically investigate root cause and what regulatory actions may be required?", why:"Sub-visible particle increases are an immunogenicity safety signal. Root causes include protein aggregation, silicone oil, tungsten, or CCS interactions.", how:"Design an investigation plan: particle characterization (MFI, Raman, FTIR), forced studies, CCS compatibility assessment.", ref:"USP <787> | USP <788> | ICH Q5C | FDA Sub-Visible Particle Guidance" },
      { id:"df08", level:"Expert", q:"What is a drug-device combination product under 21 CFR Part 3 and how do CMC development and regulatory submission requirements differ when an auto-injector is involved?", why:"Combination products require device CMC (human factors, injection force, delivery volume verification) on top of drug CMC. FDA's OCP requirements can add 12+ months.", how:"Read 21 CFR Part 3. Read ISO 11608.", ref:"21 CFR Part 3 | ISO 11608 | FDA OCP Guidance | ICH Q8" },
    ]
  },
  { id:"dom_an", label:"Analytical Methods & CQAs", icon:"📊", accent:"#A78BFA", desc:"Method development, validation, characterization, potency, HOS, MAM, OOS",
    questions:[
      { id:"da01", level:"Foundational", q:"What is N-glycosylation and how does the glycan profile of a mAb drug substance affect effector function (ADCC/CDC), pharmacokinetics, and immunogenicity?", why:"Glycosylation is the most complex and clinically consequential CQA for most mAbs.", how:"Read Jefferis 2009 review on glycosylation and antibody pharmacology.", ref:"ICH Q6B | A-Mab Case Study | Jefferis 2009 Review" },
      { id:"da02", level:"Foundational", q:"What is an OOS investigation and what are the two phases defined in FDA's 2006 guidance? What constitutes adequate Phase I vs. Phase II investigation?", why:"OOS investigations are the most cited category in FDA Warning Letters.", how:"Read FDA 2006 OOS Guidance in full. Build a Phase I/Phase II investigation flowchart.", ref:"FDA OOS Guidance (2006) | 21 CFR 211.192" },
      { id:"da03", level:"Intermediate", q:"What analytical methods characterize primary structure and higher-order structure (HOS) of a biologic, and why is HOS characterization increasingly important in BLA submissions?", why:"HOS characterization demonstrates that the biologic folds correctly — essential for potency, safety, and comparability.", how:"Read EMA reflection paper on HOS characterization.", ref:"ICH Q6B | EMA Reflection Paper on HOS | FDA Characterization Guidance" },
      { id:"da04", level:"Intermediate", q:"What is analytical ultracentrifugation (AUC) and why is it the gold standard orthogonal method for aggregate characterization compared to SEC-HPLC?", why:"AUC measures aggregation under near-native conditions without dilution or column-analyte interactions — the primary limitations of SEC.", how:"Read Berkowitz et al. on AUC for biopharmaceuticals.", ref:"ICH Q6B | USP <787> | Berkowitz et al. 2006" },
      { id:"da05", level:"Intermediate", q:"What are the key cell-based bioassay formats for mAb potency testing and what are the relative advantages and regulatory acceptance of each?", why:"Potency assay format selection is a critical analytical CMC decision. Cell-based assays are MOA-relevant but variable; binding assays are precise but may not be accepted as stand-alone.", how:"Read FDA 2008 Potency Guidance.", ref:"FDA Potency Guidance (2008) | ICH Q6B | 21 CFR 610.10" },
      { id:"da06", level:"Advanced", q:"What is the analytical comparability assessment required by ICH Q5E for a manufacturing process change, and how do you select appropriate statistical acceptance criteria for each CQA?", why:"Analytical comparability is the scientific defense that manufacturing changes are safe. Statistical acceptance criteria must be pre-defined.", how:"Read ICH Q5E. Read FDA 2003 comparability guidance.", ref:"ICH Q5E | FDA Comparability Guidance (2003) | ICH Q2(R2)" },
      { id:"da07", level:"Expert", q:"How would you design a specification-setting exercise for a new molecular entity biologic entering Phase 1, and how do specifications evolve from IND through BLA?", why:"Specification evolution from Phase 1 to BLA is one of the most important analytical CMC activities. Phase 1 specs are broad; BLA specs are tight, justified by clinical data.", how:"Read ICH Q6B Section 3. Read FDA's 2014 specification Q&A.", ref:"ICH Q6B | FDA Specification Q&A (2014) | ICH Q8" },
      { id:"da08", level:"Expert", q:"What is multi-attribute monitoring (MAM) by LC-MS and how does implementing it as a release test change the analytical control strategy and regulatory filing?", why:"MAM is a paradigm shift — one LC-MS method simultaneously monitors dozens of PTMs, replacing multiple individual methods.", how:"Read Rogers et al. 2015 and FDA 2018 MAM workshop proceedings.", ref:"FDA MAM Workshop (2018) | EMA Reflection Paper on MAM | Rogers et al. 2015" },
    ]
  },
  { id:"dom_reg", label:"Regulatory & Submissions", icon:"📋", accent:"#F59E0B", desc:"IND, BLA, CTD Module 3, FDA/EMA strategy, CRLs, ICH framework, PAI",
    questions:[
      { id:"dr01", level:"Foundational", q:"What is an IND and what CMC information is required in each section under FDA's Phase 1 IND CMC guidance?", why:"The IND is the regulatory vehicle for clinical investigation. CMC professionals must know what is required at Phase 1 to prepare an adequate package without over-investing.", how:"Read FDA Phase 1 IND CMC Guidance (2003). Build a checklist of all CMC sections.", ref:"FDA Phase 1 IND CMC Guidance (2003) | 21 CFR 312 | ICH M4Q" },
      { id:"dr02", level:"Foundational", q:"What is the CTD and how does ICH M4Q Module 3 organize the CMC information in a BLA submission?", why:"Module 3 is the CMC backbone of every BLA. Knowing the architecture fluently prevents both gaps and redundancies.", how:"Download ICH M4Q. Map every CMC deliverable to a specific CTD section number.", ref:"ICH M4Q | FDA BLA Guidance | EMA Quality CTD Guidance" },
      { id:"dr03", level:"Intermediate", q:"What are the different types of FDA meetings (Type A, B, B-Pre-Phase 3, C) and how do you structure a Type B pre-BLA meeting request to get maximally useful CMC commitments?", why:"Pre-BLA meetings prevent CRLs. Specific questions with data summaries can get FDA commitments preventing deficiencies worth 6–18 months of delay.", how:"Read FDA 2009 Formal Meetings Guidance. Draft 5 specific CMC questions for a hypothetical pre-BLA meeting.", ref:"FDA Formal Meetings Guidance (2009) | PDUFA Meeting Procedures" },
      { id:"dr04", level:"Intermediate", q:"What are the most common CMC-related reasons biologics receive Complete Response Letters (CRLs), and how does a proactive CMC development strategy prevent each failure mode?", why:"CRLs delay approval 6–18 months and cost tens of millions of dollars.", how:"Search FDA website for published CRL action letters. Identify 5 with CMC-related findings.", ref:"21 CFR 601 | FDA BLA Action Letters | FDA CDER Review Guidance" },
      { id:"dr05", level:"Advanced", q:"What is a Pre-Approval Inspection (PAI) for a biologic BLA, what areas do FDA investigators focus on, and how does a CMC leader prepare the organization?", why:"PAI is the final hurdle before approval. Most common observations: incomplete validation data, data integrity issues, inadequate OOS investigations.", how:"Read FDA PAI Compliance Program 7346.832.", ref:"FDA PAI Compliance Program 7346.832 | 21 CFR Parts 210/211 | EU GMP" },
      { id:"dr06", level:"Advanced", q:"What are the key CMC differences between FDA (BLA) and EMA (MAA) filing requirements for a biologic and how do you manage a harmonized global CMC submission?", why:"FDA and EMA have divergent expectations on batch numbering, stability protocols, comparability presentation, and process validation scope.", how:"Compare FDA BLA guidance with EMA quality dossier guidance. List 5 specific differences.", ref:"ICH M4Q | FDA BLA Guidance | EMA ICH CTD Q&A" },
      { id:"dr07", level:"Expert", q:"How do you develop a CMC regulatory strategy for a biologic entering Phase 1 today that maximizes development efficiency, minimizes BLA CMC risk, and builds in ICH Q12 lifecycle flexibility from the start?", why:"This synthesis question integrates QTPP, QbD, ICH Q12 ECs, platform strategies, and regulatory interaction planning into a coherent multi-year strategy.", how:"Draft a 2-page CMC regulatory strategy memo. Ask your mentor to critique it.", ref:"All ICH Q Guidelines | FDA Phase 1–BLA CMC Guidances | ICH Q12 | ICH M4Q" },
      { id:"dr08", level:"Expert", q:"What is Breakthrough Therapy Designation (FDA) or PRIME (EMA) and how does expedited review status change the CMC development strategy?", why:"Breakthrough/PRIME designations accelerate timelines — creating CMC pressure to compress activities that normally take years.", how:"Read FDA Breakthrough Therapy Guidance and EMA PRIME guidance.", ref:"FDA Breakthrough Therapy Guidance | EMA PRIME Guideline | 21 CFR 312.82" },
    ]
  },
  { id:"dom_val", label:"Process Validation", icon:"✅", accent:"#38BDF8", desc:"PPQ, cleaning validation, aseptic fills, Stage 1–3 lifecycle, PVLP, CPV",
    questions:[
      { id:"dv01", level:"Foundational", q:"What is the difference between process validation and process qualification, and how does FDA's 2011 lifecycle approach redefine validation as a continual activity?", why:"The 2011 guidance reframed validation from a 3-batch event to a scientific lifecycle process.", how:"Read FDA's 2011 Process Validation Guidance in full.", ref:"FDA Process Validation Guidance (2011) | ICH Q10 | ICH Q11" },
      { id:"dv02", level:"Foundational", q:"What is cleaning validation and what is the MACO calculation using a health-based exposure limit (HBEL/PDE)? Why have the old 10 ppm and 0.001-dose criteria been replaced?", why:"The old criteria are not health-based. HBEL limits are now required because they are patient-safety-justified.", how:"Read ISPE Cleaning Validation Guide. Read EMA HBEL guideline. Calculate a mock MACO.", ref:"ISPE Cleaning Validation Guide | EMA HBEL Guideline | EU GMP Annex 15" },
      { id:"dv03", level:"Intermediate", q:"What statistical approach supports the number of PPQ batches selected for a BLA and what statistical acceptance criteria are typically applied?", why:"PPQ batch number and statistical criteria must be pre-defined and scientifically justified.", how:"Read FDA 2011 PV Guidance on PPQ design. Read on tolerance intervals.", ref:"FDA Process Validation Guidance (2011) | ASTM E2281 | ICH Q8" },
      { id:"dv04", level:"Intermediate", q:"What is aseptic process validation (media fill), what are FDA expectations for media fill size and contamination rates, and how are worst-case interventions incorporated?", why:"Aseptic manufacturing failures mean sterility failures — patient deaths. Zero tolerance for contaminated units.", how:"Read FDA 2004 Aseptic Processing Guidance and EU GMP Annex 1 (2022).", ref:"FDA 2004 Aseptic Processing Guidance | EU GMP Annex 1 (2022) | USP <71>" },
      { id:"dv05", level:"Advanced", q:"What is Continued Process Verification (CPV) and what statistical tools, control chart rules, and Cpk thresholds does FDA expect?", why:"Stage 3 CPV is a perpetual regulatory obligation. FDA inspectors request CPV data and ask about trend investigations.", how:"Read FDA 2011 PV Guidance Stage 3. Learn Western Electric control chart rules.", ref:"FDA Process Validation Guidance (2011) | ASTM E2587 | ICH Q10" },
      { id:"dv06", level:"Advanced", q:"What is the validation strategy for a lyophilization process and what studies demonstrate uniformity across the lyophilizer shelf (edge, center, and corner positions)?", why:"Lyophilizer validation must demonstrate uniform product quality across all shelf positions. Edge and corner effects are well-documented phenomena.", how:"Read FDA Guidance on Lyophilized Products.", ref:"FDA Lyophilization Guidance | EU GMP Annex 15 | ICH Q8" },
      { id:"dv07", level:"Expert", q:"How would you apply process validation principles to a novel modality (mRNA/LNP or gene therapy vector) where no established platform validation approach exists?", why:"Novel modalities present unique validation challenges — no industry platform, evolving regulatory expectations.", how:"Read FDA guidance on gene therapy CMC. Read ICH Q13 on continuous manufacturing validation principles.", ref:"FDA Gene Therapy CMC Guidance | ICH Q13 | FDA mRNA Guidance" },
      { id:"dv08", level:"Expert", q:"During commercial manufacturing, Stage 3 CPV monitoring shows a sustained upward trend in bioreactor ammonia over 18 months without spec failures. What investigation steps and regulatory actions are required?", why:"Sustained upward trends without failures are the 'silent risk' in CPV — they signal drift that will eventually cause batch failure.", how:"Build a CPV trend investigation plan.", ref:"FDA Process Validation Guidance (2011) | ICH Q10 | ASTM E2587" },
    ]
  },
  { id:"dom_bio", label:"Biosimilars CMC", icon:"🔄", accent:"#4ADE80", desc:"351(k) pathway, analytical similarity tiers, reference product, interchangeability, totality of evidence",
    questions:[
      { id:"db01", level:"Foundational", q:"What is a biosimilar and how does FDA's 351(k) approval pathway differ from the 351(a) pathway? What role does CMC/analytical similarity play in the totality-of-evidence approach?", why:"Biosimilars are approved through analytical similarity + clinical extrapolation — not identical replication. CMC/analytical similarity is the centerpiece.", how:"Read FDA 2012 Biosimilar Development Guidance. Read the BPCI Act.", ref:"FDA Biosimilar Development Guidance (2012) | BPCI Act | 21 USC 351(k)" },
      { id:"db02", level:"Foundational", q:"What is reference product characterization in biosimilar development and why is it the critical first CMC step?", why:"You must understand the reference product deeply before designing your biosimilar process. The reference product's CQA distribution defines the similarity acceptance ranges.", how:"Read FDA 2019 guidance on reference product characterization.", ref:"FDA Reference Product Characterization Guidance (2019) | ICH Q6B" },
      { id:"db03", level:"Intermediate", q:"What is FDA's tiered analytical similarity assessment approach (Tiers 1, 2, and 3) and how does the tier assignment of each CQA determine the statistical rigor required?", why:"Tiered similarity testing organizes quality attributes by clinical relevance. Tier 1 requires formal equivalence testing. Tier 2 uses quality ranges. Tier 3 is descriptive.", how:"Read FDA 2019 Statistical Approaches to Analytical Similarity Guidance.", ref:"FDA Statistical Similarity Guidance (2019) | ICH Q6B | Tsong et al." },
      { id:"db04", level:"Intermediate", q:"What is interchangeability designation for a biosimilar, how does it differ from basic biosimilarity, and what studies are required?", why:"Interchangeability allows pharmacists to substitute the biosimilar without prescriber intervention — a significant commercial advantage.", how:"Read FDA 2019 Interchangeability Guidance.", ref:"FDA Interchangeability Guidance (2019) | BPCI Act" },
      { id:"db05", level:"Advanced", q:"How does a post-approval manufacturing change by the originator affect the ongoing biosimilar similarity assessment and what obligation does the biosimilar developer have?", why:"Originator post-approval changes can shift the reference product's CQA profile — changing the similarity target.", how:"Read FDA guidance on reference product characterization.", ref:"FDA Biosimilar Guidance | ICH Q12 | ICH Q5E" },
      { id:"db06", level:"Advanced", q:"What is the 'totality of evidence' standard for biosimilar approval and how do analytical similarity, PK/PD studies, and clinical safety data each contribute?", why:"Biosimilar approval is a holistic regulatory judgment. Robust analytical similarity can reduce or eliminate clinical data requirements.", how:"Read FDA's biosimilar development guidance and scientific considerations guidance.", ref:"FDA Biosimilar Scientific Considerations Guidance | FDA Biosimilar Development Guidance" },
      { id:"db07", level:"Expert", q:"How would you design a CMC development strategy for a biosimilar to a complex biologic (e.g., Fc-fusion protein with multiple glycoforms) where demonstrating analytical similarity is particularly challenging?", why:"Complex biologics have inherently higher product heterogeneity, making similarity assessment more challenging.", how:"Read FDA complex biologic biosimilar guidances.", ref:"FDA Complex Drug Biosimilar Guidance | ICH Q6B" },
      { id:"db08", level:"Expert", q:"As a CMC leader at an originator company, how does your post-approval manufacturing change strategy need to account for biosimilar competition, and what proactive CMC stewardship activities are required?", why:"Originator CMC leaders must think strategically about how manufacturing changes affect the biosimilar landscape.", how:"Read ICH Q12 on lifecycle management.", ref:"ICH Q12 | ICH Q5E | FDA Biosimilar Guidance | FDA Reference Product Guidance" },
    ]
  },
  { id:"dom_qbd", label:"Quality by Design & ICH", icon:"🎯", accent:"#F59E0B", desc:"QbD, design space, PAT, RTRT, ICH Q8–Q13 integrated framework",
    questions:[
      { id:"dq01", level:"Foundational", q:"What is Quality by Design (QbD) and how does it fundamentally differ from the traditional quality-by-testing (QbT) approach? What specific ICH Q8 tools operationalize QbD?", why:"QbD is the paradigm shift that underpins the entire modern CMC regulatory framework.", how:"Read ICH Q8(R2). Read FDA 2006 Critical Path Initiative white paper.", ref:"ICH Q8(R2) | FDA Critical Path Initiative | A-Mab Case Study" },
      { id:"dq02", level:"Foundational", q:"What is a design space in ICH Q8 and how does it differ from a proven acceptable range (PAR) and a normal operating range (NOR)?", why:"Design space is the multidimensional combination of input variables within which product quality is assured. Operating within it doesn't require a regulatory filing.", how:"Read ICH Q8 Annex on design space.", ref:"ICH Q8(R2) | FDA Process Validation Guidance | ICH Q10" },
      { id:"dq03", level:"Intermediate", q:"What is PAT per FDA's 2004 guidance and how does PAT implementation change the control strategy?", why:"PAT enables real-time monitoring and control, reducing end-product testing burden and enabling real-time release testing.", how:"Read FDA 2004 PAT Guidance.", ref:"FDA PAT Guidance (2004) | ICH Q8(R2) | ICH Q13" },
      { id:"dq04", level:"Intermediate", q:"What is the ICH Q9 Quality Risk Management framework and how are FMEA and risk ranking tools applied in CMC development programs?", why:"ICH Q9 provides the framework for systematically managing quality risks throughout the product lifecycle.", how:"Read ICH Q9. Apply FMEA to a unit operation: identify failure modes, assess severity/occurrence/detectability.", ref:"ICH Q9 | A-Mab Case Study | ICH Q8 | ICH Q11" },
      { id:"dq05", level:"Advanced", q:"What is ICH Q10 (Pharmaceutical Quality System) and how do its four elements — process performance monitoring, CAPA, change management, and management review — create a lifecycle quality management system?", why:"ICH Q10 defines the quality system framework within which all CMC development and manufacturing activities operate.", how:"Read ICH Q10 in full. Map each of its four elements to specific activities in your organization.", ref:"ICH Q10 | ICH Q8(R2) | 21 CFR Part 210/211 | EU GMP Part I" },
      { id:"dq06", level:"Advanced", q:"What is ICH Q13 on continuous manufacturing, what is the definition of 'batch' in a continuous manufacturing context, and how does process validation differ from traditional batch manufacturing?", why:"ICH Q13 (2022) is the newest addition to the ICH quality framework, addressing a manufacturing paradigm where product flows continuously.", how:"Read ICH Q13.", ref:"ICH Q13 | ICH Q8 | FDA Continuous Manufacturing Guidance" },
      { id:"dq07", level:"Expert", q:"How would you implement a fully integrated QbD program for a biologic entering Phase 1 today, and what differentiates a gold-standard QbD CMC submission from a compliance-only approach?", why:"A true QbD submission demonstrates deep process understanding, proactive risk management, and built-in lifecycle flexibility.", how:"Draft a QbD implementation plan covering: QTPP, CQA risk assessment, DoE program, control strategy, PAT, and ICH Q12 EC designation.", ref:"ICH Q8(R2) | ICH Q9 | ICH Q10 | ICH Q11 | ICH Q12 | A-Mab Case Study" },
      { id:"dq08", level:"Expert", q:"How does the concept of 'Established Conditions' (ECs) in ICH Q12 interact with the design space concept in ICH Q8, and how can a CMC leader use EC designation to maximize post-approval manufacturing flexibility?", why:"ECs are the subset of design space information that triggers a regulatory submission when changed.", how:"Read ICH Q12 Sections 2 and 3 on ECs. Read ICH Q8 Annex on design space.", ref:"ICH Q12 | ICH Q8(R2) | FDA Draft Q12 Implementation Guidance" },
    ]
  },
  { id:"dom_novel", label:"Novel Modalities", icon:"🚀", accent:"#F472B6", desc:"ADCs, mRNA/LNPs, CAR-T, gene therapy, bispecifics",
    questions:[
      { id:"dn01", level:"Foundational", q:"What is an antibody-drug conjugate (ADC) and what are the three structural components (antibody, linker, payload) whose CMC development must be independently developed and integrated?", why:"ADCs are among the most CMC-complex molecules. Each component requires independent CMC development, but all three must work together.", how:"Read FDA 2019 Guidance on ADC CMC.", ref:"FDA ADC CMC Guidance (2019) | ICH Q11 | ICH Q6B" },
      { id:"dn02", level:"Foundational", q:"What are lipid nanoparticles (LNPs) as delivery vehicles for mRNA therapeutics, and what are the unique CMC challenges for LNP manufacturing, characterization, and stability?", why:"mRNA/LNP products have unique CMC challenges: LNP encapsulation efficiency, mRNA integrity, particle size, lipid composition, and ultra-low temperature storage.", how:"Read FDA guidance on mRNA products.", ref:"FDA mRNA CMC Guidance | ICH Q11 | ICH Q6B" },
      { id:"dn03", level:"Intermediate", q:"What is Drug-to-Antibody Ratio (DAR) in an ADC, why is it a critical quality attribute, and what analytical methods measure and control DAR distribution?", why:"DAR directly affects potency, PK, and tolerability. Too high DAR causes aggregation and toxicity; too low reduces potency.", how:"Read Hamblett et al. 2004 on ADC DAR and activity.", ref:"FDA ADC CMC Guidance | ICH Q6B | Hamblett et al. 2004" },
      { id:"dn04", level:"Intermediate", q:"What are viral vector gene therapies (AAV, lentiviral), why are empty capsid ratio and vector genome titer critical quality attributes, and what manufacturing challenges affect scalability?", why:"Gene therapy viral vectors have unique CQAs (empty/full capsid ratio, VG titer, potency) and manufacturing challenges.", how:"Read FDA Gene Therapy CMC Guidance.", ref:"FDA Gene Therapy CMC Guidance | ICH Q11 | ICH Q6B" },
      { id:"dn05", level:"Intermediate", q:"What are bispecific antibodies, what are the different molecular formats, and what unique CMC challenges do bispecifics present vs. conventional mAbs?", why:"Bispecific antibodies have substantially higher CMC complexity — correct heterodimerization and separation from homodimers are required.", how:"Read Liu et al. 2017 on bispecific antibody manufacturing challenges.", ref:"FDA Bispecific Antibody CMC Guidance | ICH Q11 | ICH Q6B" },
      { id:"dn06", level:"Advanced", q:"What are CAR-T cell therapies and what unique CMC challenges arise from autologous (patient-specific) manufacturing vs. allogeneic (off-the-shelf) approaches?", why:"CAR-T autologous manufacturing creates unprecedented CMC challenges: patient-specific production, chain of identity requirements, short shelf life.", how:"Read FDA guidance on CAR-T cell therapy CMC.", ref:"FDA Cell Therapy CMC Guidance | ICH Q11 | 21 CFR 1271" },
      { id:"dn07", level:"Expert", q:"How would you develop a CMC strategy for a first-in-class bispecific T-cell engager (BiTE format) entering Phase 1, considering the unique manufacturing, characterization, and regulatory challenges?", why:"BiTE-format bispecifics have unique CMC complexity: single-chain constructs, unique purification challenges, potency assays reflecting T-cell engagement.", how:"Read FDA bispecific antibody CMC guidance.", ref:"FDA Bispecific CMC Guidance | ICH Q11 | ICH Q6B" },
      { id:"dn08", level:"Expert", q:"What is the CMC regulatory framework for RNA interference (RNAi) therapeutics (siRNA, ASOs), and how does it differ from protein biologic and small molecule regulatory pathways?", why:"RNAi therapeutics are complex synthetic oligonucleotides requiring a CMC approach distinct from both biologics and small molecules.", how:"Read FDA guidance on oligonucleotide CMC.", ref:"FDA Oligonucleotide CMC Guidance | ICH Q11 | 21 CFR 312" },
    ]
  },
  { id:"dom_lead", label:"CMC Leadership", icon:"🏆", accent:"#FCD34D", desc:"CMC strategy, career development, COGS, regulatory strategy, cross-functional communication",
    questions:[
      { id:"dl01", level:"Foundational", q:"What is a CMC development plan and how does a CMC leader build one that links all CMC activities to a BLA submission critical path?", why:"CMC is on the critical path of every drug development program. A CMC development plan maps every activity to a timeline and identifies critical path risks.", how:"Ask your mentor to show you the CMC development plan for your current program.", ref:"FDA Phase 1–BLA CMC Guidances | ICH M4Q" },
      { id:"dl02", level:"Foundational", q:"What is CMC readiness and what criteria determine whether a program is ready to advance from Phase 1 to Phase 2, Phase 2 to Phase 3, and Phase 3 to BLA?", why:"Phase-gate decisions require CMC readiness criteria. CMC leaders must know what minimum CMC package is required at each gate.", how:"Read FDA Phase 1, 2/3 CMC guidances. Build a CMC readiness checklist for each development gate.", ref:"FDA Phase 1 CMC Guidance | FDA Phase 2/3 CMC Guidance | ICH M4Q" },
      { id:"dl03", level:"Intermediate", q:"What is cost of goods (COGS) for a biologic and how do CMC development decisions made in development affect commercial manufacturing economics?", why:"CMC decisions made in development have multi-decade cost implications. CMC leaders who understand COGS make better development investment decisions.", how:"Ask your mentor to explain COGS for one of your programs.", ref:"ISPE Baseline Guides on Facility Design and COGS" },
      { id:"dl04", level:"Intermediate", q:"How does a CMC leader effectively communicate a complex technical risk to a non-technical executive team, and what framework structures this communication?", why:"CMC leaders who cannot translate scientific complexity into business decisions are career-limited.", how:"Practice the SBAR framework (Situation, Background, Assessment, Recommendation).", ref:"ICH Q9 | CMC Leadership Communication Best Practices" },
      { id:"dl05", level:"Advanced", q:"What is CMC IP strategy for a biologic and how do trade secrets vs. patents interact with regulatory disclosure requirements?", why:"CMC IP strategy is a critical intersection of science, law, and regulatory affairs. Some process knowledge disclosed in the BLA cannot be protected as a trade secret.", how:"Research 12-year data exclusivity for biologics under BPCIA.", ref:"BPCIA Section 351(k) | FDA Biological Product Exclusivity | 35 USC Patents" },
      { id:"dl06", level:"Advanced", q:"What is a CMO governance model and how do sponsor-CMO quality agreements, technical oversight, and regulatory accountability work in practice?", why:"Most biologics are manufactured at CMOs for clinical supply. Understanding the sponsor-CMO governance model is essential for CMC leaders managing external manufacturing.", how:"Read FDA guidance on contract manufacturing. Ask your mentor: how is CMO oversight structured for our programs?", ref:"FDA Contract Manufacturing Guidance | ICH Q10 | 21 CFR 211" },
      { id:"dl07", level:"Expert", q:"If starting a new Phase 1 biologic program today with a BLA target in 5 years, what are the 10 most important CMC decisions you would make in the first 90 days and why?", why:"This synthesis question marks the transition from CMC scientist to CMC leader. The answer should integrate molecular biology, process development, analytical, formulation, regulatory, and COGS.", how:"Draft a 2-page CMC strategy memo. Ask your mentor to critique it.", ref:"All ICH Q Guidelines | FDA Phase 1–BLA CMC Guidances | ICH M4Q" },
      { id:"dl08", level:"Expert", q:"A major manufacturing quality crisis (e.g., aseptic fill contamination affecting a Phase 3 batch) requires simultaneous crisis management, regulatory notification, patient safety assessment, and executive communication. How do you lead the response?", why:"Manufacturing quality crises test every dimension of CMC leadership simultaneously — scientific judgment, regulatory knowledge, risk communication.", how:"Build a crisis management playbook: first 24 hours, first 7 days, first 30 days.", ref:"21 CFR 312.32 | 21 CFR 600.14 | FDA Safety Reporting Guidance | ICH Q10" },
    ]
  },
];

export const GLOSSARY = [
  { term:"BLA", def:"Biologics License Application — the FDA regulatory submission required for approval of a biologic drug in the US. CMC information is in Module 3 of the CTD.", cat:"Regulatory" },
  { term:"IND", def:"Investigational New Drug — the regulatory application allowing a sponsor to begin clinical trials in the US. CMC content escalates from Phase 1 through Phase 3.", cat:"Regulatory" },
  { term:"CTD", def:"Common Technical Document — the standardized format for regulatory submissions globally. Module 3 contains all CMC (quality) information.", cat:"Regulatory" },
  { term:"QOS", def:"Quality Overall Summary — the reviewer-friendly narrative preceding Module 3 in a CTD submission. The first document a regulatory reviewer reads.", cat:"Regulatory" },
  { term:"PAI", def:"Pre-Approval Inspection — FDA facility inspection during BLA review to verify cGMP compliance and that submitted data accurately reflects manufacturing operations.", cat:"Regulatory" },
  { term:"PAS", def:"Prior Approval Supplement — the highest-level post-approval regulatory filing category requiring FDA review and approval before implementation.", cat:"Regulatory" },
  { term:"CBE-30", def:"Changes Being Effected (30-day notification) — a regulatory filing category for moderate-risk post-approval changes. Sponsor may implement 30 days after FDA receipt.", cat:"Regulatory" },
  { term:"PACMP", def:"Post-Approval Change Management Protocol — a pre-agreed framework with regulators (ICH Q12) for managing anticipated future manufacturing changes, potentially converting PAS to CBE-30.", cat:"Regulatory" },
  { term:"EC", def:"Established Conditions — the subset of information filed in a BLA (per ICH Q12) that triggers a regulatory submission when changed. Everything outside ECs is operational flexibility.", cat:"Regulatory" },
  { term:"APQR", def:"Annual Product Quality Review — annual compilation of all commercial batch data, OOS/OOT results, deviations, change controls, stability data, and CPV trends. Required by 21 CFR 211.180(e).", cat:"Quality" },
  { term:"QTPP", def:"Quality Target Product Profile — a prospective summary of desired quality characteristics of a drug product ensuring desired quality, safety, and efficacy. The foundation of QbD.", cat:"QbD" },
  { term:"CQA", def:"Critical Quality Attribute — a physical, chemical, biological, or microbiological property that must be within an appropriate limit to ensure desired product quality, safety, and efficacy.", cat:"QbD" },
  { term:"CPP", def:"Critical Process Parameter — a process parameter whose variability has an impact on a CQA and therefore should be monitored or controlled to produce the desired quality.", cat:"QbD" },
  { term:"KPP", def:"Key Process Parameter — a parameter that affects process performance (yield, cycle time) but has no demonstrated impact on CQAs within the studied range.", cat:"QbD" },
  { term:"NOR", def:"Normal Operating Range — the target parameter range used in routine manufacturing. Narrower than the PAR, providing a guard band against specification failure.", cat:"QbD" },
  { term:"PAR", def:"Proven Acceptable Range — the wider range of a CPP demonstrated safe and effective by process characterization data. Operating within PAR does not require a regulatory filing.", cat:"QbD" },
  { term:"DoE", def:"Design of Experiments — a structured statistical approach to studying effects of multiple input variables simultaneously. Captures interaction effects that OFAT cannot.", cat:"QbD" },
  { term:"FMEA", def:"Failure Mode and Effects Analysis — a risk management tool analyzing potential failure modes (severity × occurrence × detectability) to prioritize risk mitigation.", cat:"QbD" },
  { term:"PAT", def:"Process Analytical Technology — a system for designing, analyzing, and controlling manufacturing through timely measurements of critical quality and performance attributes.", cat:"QbD" },
  { term:"MCB", def:"Master Cell Bank — a collection of cells of uniform composition prepared from a single source, stored under defined conditions. The irreplaceable genetic reference for the product.", cat:"Cell Science" },
  { term:"WCB", def:"Working Cell Bank — derived from one or more vials of the MCB, used for the production of all manufactured batches throughout the product lifecycle.", cat:"Cell Science" },
  { term:"PDL", def:"Population Doublings Limit — the number of cell population doublings from the MCB to end of production, used to express the extent of genetic stability studies.", cat:"Cell Science" },
  { term:"EOP", def:"End of Production — cells at the limit of the manufacturing duration, used to demonstrate genetic stability across the full production cycle.", cat:"Cell Science" },
  { term:"qP", def:"Specific Productivity — the rate of product formation per cell per unit time (pg/cell/day). A measure of cell-level efficiency independent of culture density.", cat:"Cell Science" },
  { term:"HCP", def:"Host Cell Proteins — proteins derived from the host cell used in manufacturing. A critical process-related impurity with immunogenicity and product stability implications.", cat:"Manufacturing" },
  { term:"Protein A", def:"A bacterial surface protein (from Staphylococcus aureus) used in chromatography to selectively capture mAbs via Fc region binding. The first and most important purification step.", cat:"Manufacturing" },
  { term:"LRF", def:"Log Reduction Factor — a measure of viral load reduction achieved by a process step. Calculated as log10(input virus titer / output virus titer).", cat:"Manufacturing" },
  { term:"UF/DF", def:"Ultrafiltration/Diafiltration — membrane filtration technique to concentrate and buffer-exchange purified drug substance to the formulation buffer at target concentration.", cat:"Manufacturing" },
  { term:"kLa", def:"Volumetric Mass Transfer Coefficient — a measure of oxygen transfer efficiency in a bioreactor. Critical for DO control and the primary scale-up challenge parameter.", cat:"Manufacturing" },
  { term:"CEX", def:"Cation Exchange Chromatography — binds positively charged proteins at low salt. Used in bind-elute mode for aggregate and HCP removal in polishing.", cat:"Manufacturing" },
  { term:"AEX", def:"Anion Exchange Chromatography — binds negatively charged impurities (DNA, endotoxin, viruses). Used in flow-through mode in mAb purification.", cat:"Manufacturing" },
  { term:"SEC", def:"Size-Exclusion Chromatography — separates molecules by size. Primary analytical method for aggregate and fragment characterization, with known limitations (dilution artifacts).", cat:"Analytical" },
  { term:"AUC", def:"Analytical Ultracentrifugation — biophysical technique for accurate aggregate and fragment quantification under near-native conditions. The gold standard orthogonal method to SEC.", cat:"Analytical" },
  { term:"icIEF", def:"Imaged Capillary Isoelectric Focusing — electrophoretic technique separating protein species by isoelectric point. Used for charge variant analysis of biologics.", cat:"Analytical" },
  { term:"MAM", def:"Multi-Attribute Monitoring — LC-MS based peptide mapping approach that simultaneously monitors multiple quality attributes (deamidation, oxidation, glycosylation) in a single analysis.", cat:"Analytical" },
  { term:"DAR", def:"Drug-to-Antibody Ratio — the average number of drug molecules conjugated per antibody in an ADC. A critical quality attribute affecting potency, PK, and safety.", cat:"Analytical" },
  { term:"OOS", def:"Out-of-Specification — a test result falling outside the established acceptance criteria. Requires Phase I (lab) and potentially Phase II (manufacturing) investigation per FDA 2006 guidance.", cat:"Quality" },
  { term:"OOT", def:"Out-of-Trend — a test result within specification but showing a concerning trend compared to historical data. Requires investigation and trending assessment per ICH Q10.", cat:"Quality" },
  { term:"CAPA", def:"Corrective and Preventive Action — actions taken to eliminate causes of an existing nonconformity and prevent recurrence. A core element of ICH Q10.", cat:"Quality" },
  { term:"PPQ", def:"Process Performance Qualification — Stage 2 of FDA's process validation lifecycle. Commercial-scale confirmation that the process design consistently produces acceptable product.", cat:"Validation" },
  { term:"CPV", def:"Continued Process Verification — Stage 3 of FDA's process validation lifecycle. Ongoing statistical monitoring of commercial manufacturing using control charts and Cpk/Ppk analysis.", cat:"Validation" },
  { term:"MACO", def:"Maximum Allowable Carryover — the maximum amount of residual product allowed in equipment after cleaning. Calculated using health-based exposure limits (PDE/ADE).", cat:"Validation" },
  { term:"SDM", def:"Scale-Down Model — a smaller-scale bioreactor or unit operation demonstrated to be representative of commercial manufacturing scale. All process characterization studies are conducted in the qualified SDM.", cat:"Validation" },
  { term:"PDE", def:"Permitted Daily Exposure — a health-based exposure limit used in cleaning validation MACO calculations. Replaces arbitrary 10 ppm and 0.001-dose criteria with toxicologically-justified limits.", cat:"Validation" },
  { term:"ADC", def:"Antibody-Drug Conjugate — a biologic consisting of a monoclonal antibody linked to a cytotoxic drug via a linker. One of the most CMC-complex molecular modalities.", cat:"Novel Modalities" },
  { term:"LNP", def:"Lipid Nanoparticle — a delivery vehicle for mRNA therapeutics, consisting of ionizable lipid, phospholipid, cholesterol, and PEGylated lipid. Requires ultra-low temperature storage.", cat:"Novel Modalities" },
  { term:"CAR-T", def:"Chimeric Antigen Receptor T-cell therapy — an autologous cell therapy where a patient's T-cells are genetically engineered to express a cancer-specific CAR. Creates unprecedented chain-of-identity CMC challenges.", cat:"Novel Modalities" },
];
